rv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Schaffner|first=Alain |title=Albert Camus: l'exigence morale : hommage \u00e0 Jacqueline L\u00e9vi-Valensi (L'esprit des lettres)|editor=Agn\u00e8s Spiquel  |publisher=Editions Le Manuscrit|year=2006 |isbn=2748171012|via=Google Books |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=peseTi-X8FoC|language=French|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Sharpe|first=Matthew |authorlink=Matthew Sharpe|title=Camus, Philosophe: To Return to our Beginnings|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pdZ0CgAAQBAJ&pg=PA9|date=3 September 2015|publisher=[[Brill Publishers|BRILL]]|isbn=978-90-04-30234-1|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Sherman|first=David |title=Camus|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=X2zuGq1BCBYC|date=30 January 2009|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-1-4443-0328-5|ref=harv}} \n* {{cite encyclopedia|last=Simpson|first=David|title=Albert Camus (1913\u20131960)|encyclopedia= [[The Internet Encyclopedia of Philosophy]]|year=2019 |url= https://www.iep.utm.edu/camus/|issn=2161-0002 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book|last=Todd|first=Olivier |authorlink=Oliver Todd|title=Albert Camus: A Life |publisher=[[Carroll & Graf]] |year=2000 |isbn=978-0-7867-0739-3|ref=harv}} \n* {{Cite news |last=Willsher |first=Kim |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2011/aug/07/albert-camus-killed-by-kgb |title=Albert Camus might have been killed by the KGB for criticising the Soviet Union, claims newspaper |date=7 August 2011 |work=The Guardian |access-date=13 June 2019|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite magazine|last=Zaretsky|first=Robert|url=https://lareviewofbooks.org/article/no-longer-the-person-i-was-the-dazzling-correspondence-of-albert-camus-and-maria-casares/#!|title='No Longer the Person I Was': The Dazzling Correspondence of Albert Camus and Maria Casar\u00e8s|magazine=[[Los Angeles Review of Books]]|year=2018|accessdate=13 April 2018|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Zaretsky|first=Robert |title=A Life Worth Living|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PQjeAAAAQBAJ|date=7 November 2013|publisher=[[Harvard University Press]]|isbn=978-0-674-72837-0|ref=harv}}\n\n==Further reading==\n===Selected biographies===\n<!--extensive 'further reading' removed 2015-09-20, see history - largely non-English-->\n* {{cite book|last=Thody|first=Philip Malcolm Waller|author-link=Philip Thody|title=Albert Camus: A Study of His Work|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NmAzAAAAMAAJ|year=1957|publisher=[[Hamish Hamilton]]}}\n* {{cite book|last=Brisville|first=Jean-Claude|authorlink=Jean-Claude Brisville|title=Camus|url=https://archive.org/details/camus0000bris|url-access=registration|year=1959|publisher=[[Gallimard]]}}\n* {{cite book|last=Parker|first=Emmett |title=Albert Camus: The Artist in the Arena|url=https://archive.org/details/albertcamusartis00park|url-access=registration|year=1965|publisher=[[Univ of Wisconsin Press]]|isbn=978-0-299-03554-9}}\n* {{cite book|last=King|first=Adele |authorlink=Adele King|title=Albert Camus|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CmQoAQAAIAAJ|year=1964|publisher=[[Grove Press]]}}\n* {{cite book|last=McCarthy|first=Patrick |title=Camus: A Critical Study of His Life and Work|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VJNcAAAAMAAJ|year=1982|publisher=Hamish Hamilton|isbn=978-0-241-10603-7}}\n* {{cite book|last=Sprintzen|first=David |title=Camus: A Critical Examination|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ugWANQAACAAJ|date=February 1991|publisher=[[Temple University Press]]|isbn=978-0-87722-827-1}}\n* {{cite book|last=King|first=Adele |authorlink=Adele King|title=Camus's L'Etranger: Fifty Years on|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FQexCwAAQBAJ|date=12 June 1992|publisher=[[Palgrave Macmillan]] UK|isbn=978-1-349-22003-8}}\n* {{cite book|last=Bloom|first=Harold |authorlink=Harold Bloom|title=Albert Camus|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ihqHSbg41TUC|year=2009|publisher=[[Infobase Publishing]]|isbn=978-1-4381-1515-3}}\n* {{cite book|author=Pierre Louis Rey|title=Camus: l'homme r\u00e9volt\u00e9|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nFRlAAAAMAAJ|year=2006|publisher=Gallimard|isbn=978-2-07-031828-5}}\n* {{cite book|last=Hawes|first=Elizabeth |authorlink=Elizabeth Hawes|title=Camus, a Romance|url=https://archive.org/details/camusromance00hawe|url-access=registration|year=2009|publisher=[[Grove Press]]|isbn=978-0-8021-1889-9}}\n* {{cite book|last=Carroll|first=Sean B. |authorlink=Sean B. Carroll|title=Brave Genius: A Scientist, a Philosopher, and Their Daring Adventures from the French Resistance to the Nobel Prize|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XchvDwAAQBAJ|year=2013|publisher=[[Crown Publishers]]|isbn=978-0-307-95234-9}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://camusbibliography.boisestate.edu/ Albert Camus. Selective and Cumulative Bibliography]\n*[http://www.uflib.ufl.edu/spec/camus/<nowiki/>Raymond Gay-Crosier Camus collection] at University of Florida Library\n*[http://www.camus-society.com/ Albert Camus Society UK]\n\n{{Camus}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title=Articles related to Albert Camus\n|list=\n{{The Stranger (Camus novel)}}\n{{Nobel Prize in Literature Laureates 1951-1975}}\n{{Continental philosophy}}\n{{Existentialism}}\n{{Social and political philosophy}}\n{{Anarchism}}\n}}\n{{Portal bar|France|Biography}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Camus, Albert}}\n[[Category:Albert Camus| ]]\n[[Category:1913 births]]\n[[Category:1960 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century atheists]]\n[[Category:20th-century French essayists]]\n[[Category:20th-century French dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:20th-century French male writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century French novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century French philosophers]]\n[[Category:20th-century short story writers]]\n[[Category:Anarcho-communists]]\n[[Category:Anarcho-pacifists]]\n[[Category:Anarcho-syndicalists]]\n[[Category:Anti-capitalists]]\n[[Category:Anti-fascists]]\n[[Category:Anti-Stalinist left]]\n[[Category:Communist members of the French Resistance]]\n[[Category:Continental philosophers]]\n[[Category:French anarchists]]\n[[Category:French anti\u2013death penalty activists]]\n[[Category:French atheists]]\n[[Category:French Communist Party members]]\n[[Category:French communists]]\n[[Category:French expatriates in Algeria]]\n[[Category:French humanists]]\n[[Category:French journalists]]\n[[Category:French Marxists]]\n[[Category:French Nobel laureates]]\n[[Category:French pacifists]]\n[[Category:French people of Spanish descent]]\n[[Category:French Resistance members]]\n[[Category:French socialists]]\n[[Category:Left-libertarians]]\n[[Category:Libertarian socialists]]\n[[Category:L\u00e9gion d'honneur refusals]]\n[[Category:French male essayists]]\n[[Category:Modernist writers]]\n[[Category:Nobel laureates in Literature]]\n[[Category:People from Dr\u00e9an]]\n[[Category:Pieds-Noirs]]\n[[Category:Road incident deaths in France]]\n[[Category:University of Algiers alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Cinadon36", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNon-fiction books:backspace", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Albert_Camus"}
{"title_page": "Forces Goal 2030", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=April 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n\n[[File:\u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be\u09a6\u09c7\u09b6 \u09b8\u09be\u09ae\u09b0\u09bf\u0995 \u09ac\u09be\u09b9\u09bf\u09a8\u09c0\u09b0 \u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u09a4\u09c0\u0995.svg|200px|thumb|right|Emblem of Bangladesh Armed Forces]]\n'''Forces Goal 2030''' is the current long-term modernization program of the [[Bangladesh Armed Forces]] which began in 2009. The primary focus of the modernization program is to reform the military organization and training, expand the size of the forces, acquire modern weapons, and develop indigenous defense industries.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://thediplomat.com/2018/01/bangladeshs-ambitious-military-modernization-drive/|author=Shakil Bin Mushtaq|title=Bangladesh's Ambitious Military Modernization Drive|place=Bangladesh |date=2018-01-09|accessdate=2019-04-23}}</ref>\n\n==Plans and developments==\n===Army===\nForces Goal 2030 aims to make [[Bangladesh Army]] a well-trained, well-armed and technologically advanced force that can defend the country from any conventional and unconventional threats. The Bangladesh Army planned to conduct its activities under three independent corps \u2013 Central, Eastern and Western.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theindependentbd.com/printversion/details/32722|title=Army plans to work under three corps|last=Independent|first=The|access-date=28 August 2016}}</ref> Three new infantry divisions, the [[17th Infantry Division (Bangladesh)|17th infantry division]] at [[Sylhet District|Sylhet]],<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.dhakatribune.com/bangladesh/2013/sep/18/pm-launches-17-infantry-division| title=PM launches 17 Infantry Division| publisher=Dhaka Tribune| accessdate=21 September 2015}}</ref> [[10th Infantry Division (Bangladesh)|10th infantry division]] at Ramu in [[Cox's Bazar District|Cox's Bazar]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bssnews.net/newsDetails.php?cat=0&id=474604&date=2015-03-01 |title=PM urges army to remain prepared against any threat to democracy |publisher=Bangladesh Sangbad Sangstha |date= |accessdate=8 February 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161128184650/http://www.bssnews.net/newsDetails.php?cat=0&id=474604&date=2015-03-01 |archive-date=28 November 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and [[7th Infantry Division (Bangladesh)|7th infantry division]] at [[Barishal District|Barishal]]-[[Patuakhali District|Patuakhali]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dhakatribune.com/bangladesh/nation/2018/02/08/pm-reaches-patuakhali/|title=PM inaugurates Sheikh Hasina Cantonment in Patuakhali|publisher=Dhakatribune|date=8 February 2018|accessdate=8 February 2018}}</ref> have been raised to make the number of total infantry divisions ten. A Riverine Engineer Battalion is also going to be formed under a proposed cantonment at Mithamoine in Kishorganj.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.theindependentbd.com/home/printnews/104318| title=Army to get 97 more units in 4 years | publisher=The Independent| date=16 July 2017|accessdate=11 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.janes.com/article/72633/bangladesh-army-to-get-97-more-units-in-four-years-says-report| title=Bangladesh Army to get 97 more units in four years, says report| publisher=Jane's 360| date=26 July 2017|accessdate=11 August 2017}}</ref> A full-fledged cantonment is being established at [[Ruma Upazila|Ruma]] of [[Bandarban District]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.theindependentbd.com/arcprint/details/52702/2016-07-25|title=Focus on 1971 spirit, says PM|last=Independent|first=The|newspaper=Focus on 1971 spirit, says PM {{!}} theindependentbd.com|access-date=1 December 2016}}</ref> Government has a plan to add 97 new units within 2021. Of them, 19 units  will be formed for the Sylhet Cantonment, 22 for the Ramu Cantonment and 56 units for the Sheikh Hasina Cantonment in Lebukhali. Process of converting some regular infantry battalions into [[Paratrooper|para infantry]] battalions and [[mechanized infantry]] battalions is also going on.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bssnews.net/newsDetails.php?cat=0&id=742740&date=2018-05-13 |title=Stay alert to face internal & external threats |publisher=[[Bangladesh Sangbad Sangstha]] |date=13 May 2018 |accessdate=16 May 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180517152948/http://www.bssnews.net/newsDetails.php?cat=0&id=742740&date=2018-05-13 |archive-date=17 May 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> To increase special operation capabilities, ''2nd Commando Battalion'' has been raised. This battalion together with the ''1st Commando Battalion'' formed the sole [[Para-Commando Brigade (Bangladesh)|Para-Commando Brigade]] of the country.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.thedailystar.net/backpage/dhaka-cafe-attack-recounting-operation-thunderbolt-1427413| title=Recounting 'Operation Thunderbolt'| publisher=The Daily Star| date=3 July 2017| accessdate=11 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Bangladesh Army modular infantry. (30801511334).jpg|200px|thumb|right|New outfit of Bangladeshi infantry.]]\n\nSeveral steps has been taken to modernize the regular infantry outfits. The infantry soldiers are being equipped with modern gear like [[Night vision device|Night Vision Goggles (NVG)]], [[SPECTRA helmet|Ballistic helmets]], [[Ballistic eyewear|Eye protective gear]], [[Bulletproof vest]], person to person communicators, [[palmtop]] [[GPS navigation device|GPS device]] and [[Type 81 assault rifle|BD-08]] assault rifles with [[Collimator sight]]. To strengthen the mechanized infantry units, around 650 [[BTR-80]] APCs, 50 [[Otokar Cobra|Otokar Cobra I]] LAVs, 50 [[Otokar Cobra|Otokar Cobra II]] MRAPs and several [[BOV M11]] armoured reconnaissance vehicles have been added. To enhance the anti-tank capabilities, [[9K115-2 Metis-M|Metis-M]] missile systems, [[PF-98]] rocket systems and [[RPG-7|RPG-7V2]] [[Rocket-propelled grenade]]s were procured. Evaluation process of modern [[assault rifle]]s and [[submachine gun]]s is also going on.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://dgdp.gov.bd/dgdp/AP_TEN/notice/411.pdf|title=Evaluation of suitable small arms/assault riffle/sub-machine gun for Bangladesh Army| publisher=DGDP| accessdate=10 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe firepower of artillery units was increased by procuring [[Nora B-52|Nora B-52 K2]] self-propelled artillery systems. Four regiment of [[Weishi Rockets#WS-22|WS-22]] Guided Multiple Rocket Launcher System were also added. In 2019, army signed contract to procure one regiment of [[Kasirga rocket system|T-300 Kasirga]] MLRS system from Turkey.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.savunmahaber.com/en/brigadier-general-md-tariqul-alam-tariq-the-defence-attache-of-bangladesh-to-turkey-turkish-companies-are-winning-the-tenders-for-product-compatibility-lower-price-and-easy-after-sale-serv/|title=Brigadier General Md Tariqul Alam TARIQ, the Defence Attach\u00e9 of Bangladesh to Turkey: \"Turkish companies are winning the tenders for product compatibility, lower price and easy after sale service.\"| publisher=MSI Turkish Defence Review| date=31 March 2020|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref> [[SLC-2 Radar|SLC-2]] weapon locating radars were added to help the artillery firing. Procurement process of 155mm towed howitzer,<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.dgdp.gov.bd/dgdp/AP_TEN/notice/359.pdf| title=Evaluation of 155mm Howitzer| publisher=dgdp| date=24 September 2017| accessdate=24 November 2017}}</ref> 122&nbsp;mm field artillery howitzers<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.dgdp.gov.bd/dgdp/AP_TEN/notice/374.pdf| title=Evaluation of 122mm Howitzer| publisher=dgdp| date=21 November 2017| accessdate=24 November 2017}}</ref> and 105mm towed field artillery systems is going on.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.dgdp.gov.bd/dgdp/AP_TEN/notice/373.pdf| title=Procurement of 105mm howitzer| publisher=dgdp| date=| accessdate=25 November 2017}}</ref> Procurement of long range [[Multiple rocket launcher|multiple launch rocket system (MLRS)]] is also in the process.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://dgdp.gov.bd/dgdp/AP_TEN/notice/410.pdf|title=Evaluation of multiple launch rocket system Type A|publisher=DGDP|accessdate=10 April 2018}}</ref> To support accurate artillery firing, Bangladesh Army has procured 36 ''Bramor C4EYE'' battlefield reconnaissance UAV from Slovenia in 2017. These UAVs have a maximum range of 40 kilometres and endurance of 3 hours.\n\nThe Bangladesh Army procured 44 [[Al-Khalid tank|MBT-2000]] tanks from China in 2011. Army engineers have completed the upgradation process of [[Type 69/79 main battle tank|Type 69 tank]]s to ''Type 69IIG'' standard.<ref name=\"thedailystar\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/city/modernisation-army-continue-89149|title=Modernisation of army to continue|date=29 May 2015|work=The Daily Star|access-date=8 December 2017}}</ref> Upgradation of 174 [[Type 59 tank]]s to [[Type 59 tank#Foreign variants|Type 59G Durjoy]] standard is going on.<ref>{{cite news |date=28 May 2015 |title=Prime Minister Hasina expects greater involvement of army in development efforts |url=http://bdnews24.com/bangladesh/2015/05/28/prime-minister-hasina-expects-greater-involvement-of-army-in-development-efforts |newspaper=bdnews24.com}}</ref> Bangladesh Army has signed contract with China for 44 [[Type 15 tank|VT-5]] light tanks in 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eng.chinamil.com.cn/view/2019-12/20/content_9700539.htm|title=Bangladesh Navy receives two Chinese frigates|publisher=Chinamil|date=20 December 2019|accessdate=28 December 2019}}</ref> Army also started amphibious light procurement process in 2019.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://dgdp.gov.bd/dgdp/AP_TEN/notice/539.pdf| title=Standardization of light amphibious tank (tracked) and amph armoured repair and recovery vehicle (tracked) for Bangladesh Army| publisher=dgdp| date=23 April 2019| accessdate=30 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nTwo regiments of [[HQ-7#HQ-7A .28FM-90.29|FM 90C]] short range [[surface to air missile]] were added in 2016 to enhance air defence capabilities.<ref name=\"thedailystar\"/> In 2017, two [[Oerlikon GDF|Oerlikon GDF 009]] [[Anti-aircraft warfare|anti aircraft gun]] systems have been procured with Skyguard fire control radar.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://dgdp.gov.bd/dgdp/AP_TEN/s_doc/2615.pdf|title=TECHNICAL SPECIFICATION AND OTHER REQUIREMENTS FOR ITEM SER NO 1. CARTS HIGH EXPLOSIVE INCENDIARY (HEI) FOR RADAR CONTROL AIR DEFENCE GUN SYSTEM 35 MM OERLIKON GDF 009/SKYGURAD 3,QTY-1,000 NOS|publisher=DGDP|accessdate=3 September 2019}}</ref> In March 2018, a tender was floated for two local warning radars. The models shortlisted for the tender are [[Ground Master 400]] of [[Thales Group|Thales]], ''TRML 3D/32'' of [[Hensoldt]] and ''KRONOS Land'' of [[Leonardo S.p.A.|Leonardo]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dgdp.gov.bd/dgdp/AP_TEN/s_doc/2229.pdf|title=Tender specification of Local Warning Radar|publisher=DGDP|accessdate=24 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180324224420/http://dgdp.gov.bd/dgdp/AP_TEN/s_doc/2229.pdf|archive-date=24 March 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> In the same month, another tender was issued for procuring 181 [[Man-portable air-defense system]]s. Here, Chinese [[FN-6#FN-16|FN-16]], Russian [[9K38 Igla|Igla-S]] and Swedish [[RBS 70]] systems has been shortlisted.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://dgdp.gov.bd/dgdp/AP_TEN/a_doc/2192.pdf|title=Tender for surface to air missile|publisher=DGDP|accessdate=24 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Bangladesh Army LCT Shakti Shanchar (26749862156).jpg|200px|thumb|right|Bangladesh Army LCT Shakti Shanchar]]\n\nModernizing the army aviation wing is in full swing. Two [[Eurocopter AS365 Dauphin]]s were put into service in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.infodefensa.com/latam/2012/11/28/comunicado-eurocopter-as365-n3-dauphin-helicopters-enter-service-with-the-bangladesh-army-for-use-in-humanitarian-missions-and-vip-airlift.html|title=Eurocopter AS365 N3+ Dauphin helicopters enter service with the Bangladesh Army for use in humanitarian missions and VIP airlift.|publisher=infodefensa.com|date=|accessdate=29 May 2015}}</ref> Six [[Mil Mi-17#Variants|Mil Mi-171Sh]] helicopters were procured from Russia in 2016. One [[EADS CASA C-295|C-295]] transport aircraft was bought from Spain. Army Aviation has plan to add one more [[EADS CASA C-295]] transport aircraft and six more [[Mil Mi-17|Mil Mi-171Sh]] helicopters to its fleet soon. They also have a plan to add [[attack helicopter]]s to the fleet in the near future.<ref name =\"aagdev\">{{cite web| url=https://mzamin.com/article.php?mzamin=203653| title=\u09ae\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09be\u09a8\u09ae\u09be\u09b0\u0995\u09c7 \u09ac\u09b2\u09c7\u099b\u09bf \u09b0\u09cb\u09b9\u09bf\u0999\u09cd\u0997\u09be\u09a6\u09c7\u09b0 \u09ab\u09bf\u09b0\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09c7 \u09a8\u09c7\u09af\u09bc\u09be\u09b0 \u09b8\u09ac \u09ac\u09cd\u09af\u09ac\u09b8\u09cd\u09a5\u09be \u09a4\u09be\u09a6\u09c7\u09b0\u0995\u09c7 \u0995\u09b0\u09a4\u09c7 \u09b9\u09ac\u09c7 |language=bn | publisher=Daily Manab Zamin| date=13 December 2019| accessdate=14 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nTender was floated for procurement of a command ship in 2017. The vessel will be used as a floating command centre for different waterborne operations.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.dgdp.gov.bd/dgdp/AP_TEN/s_doc/997.pdf| title=Tender specification of vessel Type C (comd. vessel)| publisher=dgdp| accessdate=18 February 2017| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170219095610/http://www.dgdp.gov.bd/dgdp/AP_TEN/s_doc/997.pdf| archive-date=19 February 2017| url-status=dead}}</ref> Several tenders were floated to procure a total of six [[Landing craft tank]] for the army between 2017 and 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dailyasianage.com/news/71502/wms-to-build-two-combat-tank-carriers-for-army|title=WMS to build two combat tank carriers for Army|publisher=The Daily Asian Age|date=5 July 2017|accessdate=5 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170808075406/http://dailyasianage.com/news/71502/wms-to-build-two-combat-tank-carriers-for-army|archive-date=8 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.dgdp.gov.bd/dgdp/AP_TEN/s_doc/2089.pdf| title=Technical specification of vessel Type A| publisher=DGDP| accessdate=2 February 2018| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180203064247/http://www.dgdp.gov.bd/dgdp/AP_TEN/s_doc/2089.pdf| archive-date=3 February 2018| url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://dgdp.gov.bd/dgdp/AP_TEN/s_doc/2261.pdf| title=Technical specification of vessel Type A| publisher=DGDP| accessdate=23 April 2018| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180424072134/http://dgdp.gov.bd/dgdp/AP_TEN/s_doc/2261.pdf| archive-date=24 April 2018| url-status=dead}}</ref> Bangladesh army issued tender for procuring two ''[[Troopship|Troops Carrier Vessel (TCV)]]'' in January 2018. The vessels will be able to carry 200 personnel.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://dgdp.gov.bd/dgdp/AP_TEN/s_doc/2082.pdf| title=Technical specification of vessel Type B| publisher=DGDP| accessdate=2 February 2018| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180202190531/http://dgdp.gov.bd/dgdp/AP_TEN/s_doc/2082.pdf| archive-date=2 February 2018| url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Navy===\nForces goal 2030 includes plan to  make the [[Bangladesh Navy]] a well-equipped three dimensional navy that can protect the maritime interests of Bangladesh. Modernization and expansion of the force is going on simultaneously. Bangladesh Navy is setting up a submarine base named [[BNS Sheikh Hasina]], at Pekua in [[Cox's Bazar]].<ref>{{cite news |date=12 October 2013 |title=Work started for land acquisition for submarine base: PM |url=http://primenews.com.bd/details/17340 |newspaper=Prime News |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140519185247/http://primenews.com.bd/details/17340 |archive-date=19 May 2014}}</ref> The largest naval base of the country is under construction at Rabanabad in [[Patuakhali]] named [[BNS Sher-e-Bangla]]. The base will have submarine berthing and aviation facilities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theindependentbd.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=233041:largest-naval-base-to-be-in-patuakhali-pm&catid=132:backpage&Itemid=122|title=Largest naval base to be in Patuakhali: PM|author=Shorwar Hossain|accessdate=24 December 2014}}</ref> A full-fledged operational base, named ''BNS Sheikh Mujib'', has been constructed in Khilkhet of Dhaka.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bssnews.net/?p=115568|title=PM commissions naval base \u2018BNS Sheikh Mujib\u2019|website=bssnews.net| accessdate=28 December 2019}}</ref> The construction works of a fleet headquarters at the Sandwip channel of Chattogram with ship berthing facilities is also going on.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://unb.com.bd/bangladesh-news/One-day-BD-Navy-to-become-builder-from-buyer-hopes-PM/59066|title=One day BD Navy to become builder from buyer, hopes PM|publisher=UNB|date=24 December 2017|accessdate=24 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171225035005/http://unb.com.bd/bangladesh-news/One-day-BD-Navy-to-become-builder-from-buyer-hopes-PM/59066|archive-date=25 December 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> Navy has taken initiative to make missiles and [[Identification friend or foe|IFF]] system in Bangladesh.<ref name=\"pm\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ispr.gov.bd/en/honourable-prime-minister-shiekh-hasina-reviewed-the-winter-president-parade-at-bangladesh-neval-academybns-chottagram/ |title=Honourable Prime Minister Shiekh Hasina Reviewed the Winter President Parade at Bangladesh Neval Academy(BNS), Chottagram |publisher=ISPR |date=22 December 2019 |accessdate=28 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nNavy's surface combatants are being increased with the induction of new and refurbished vessels. Two refurbished Chinese [[Type 053 frigate#Type 053H2 .28Jianghu-III.29 Ships of Class|Type 053H2 frigate]]s were bought and commissioned in 2014. The [[US Coast Guard]] provided two [[Hamilton class cutter|Hamilton class]] high endurance cutters, now serving as patrol and training frigates. Two Ex-[[Royal Navy]] [[Castle-class patrol vessel]]s were equipped with anti-ship missiles to serve as corvettes. To enhance surveying capacity, BN purchased an Ex-[[Royal Navy]] survey ship, commissioned as [[BNS Anushandhan]]. Navy has recently got the delivery of two refurbished [[ Type 053H3 frigate]]s which will be commissioned soon. Two more frigates of the same class has been ordered from the Chinese stock.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.janes.com/article/93346/china-hands-over-two-ex-plan-frigates-to-bangladeshi-navy| title=China hands over two ex-PLAN frigates to Bangladeshi Navy| publisher=Janes 360| date=20 December 2019| accessdate=26 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nTwo [[Type 056 corvette]]s were bought from China and commissioned in 2016. Two more corvettes of the same class have been delivered and awating commissioning.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2019-04/03/c_137947179.htm |title = CSIC builds two light frigates for Bangladesh |publisher = [[Xinhua News Agency|Xinhua]] |date= 3 April 2019 |accessdate = 4 April 2019}}</ref> Navy acquired two [[anti-surface warfare]] capable [[Durjoy-class LPC]]s in 2013 from China. Two more Durjoy class vessels with [[anti-submarine warfare]] capabilities were built at [[Khulna Shipyard]] and commissioned in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dhakatribune.com/bangladesh/2017/11/08/president-hamid-navy-ship-commissioning/| title=President Hamid commissions four new naval ships| publisher=The Dhaka Tribune|date= 8 November 2017| accessdate=9 November 2017}}</ref> [[Khulna Shipyard]] also built five [[Padma-class Patrol Vessel]]s which were commissioned in 2013. Currently, five more ships of the same class are under construction there. Khulna Shipyard is constructing two [[Research vessel|hydrographic research ships]] for the Bangladesh Navy. Two coastal survey vessels are under construction at [[Dockyard and Engineering Works Limited]]. Several [[Landing Craft Utility|LCU]]s and [[Landing craft tank|LCT]]s were also built at Khulna Shipyard and Dockyard and Engineering Works Limited. An oil tanker made by [[Ananda Shipyard and Shipways|Ananda Shipyard]] was commissioned in 2015. [[Chattogram Dry Dock Limited]] is in talks with different foreign shipbuilders for the constructing six frigates in collaboration with them.<ref name=\"pm\"/> The process is going on for procuring more [[corvette]]s, [[minesweeper]]s, oceanographic research ship and sail training ship is going on.<ref name=\"pm\"/>\n\n[[File:Dornier Do-228 MPA of Bangladesh Navy.jpg|200px|thumb|right|Dornier Do-228 MPA of Bangladesh Navy.]]\n\nThe Bangladesh Navy inaugurated its aviation wing with the induction of two [[AgustaWestland AW109]] helicopters in 2011. In 2013, two [[Dornier Do 228|Dornier Do 228 NG]] [[maritime patrol aircraft]] were added to the fleet. Two more Dornier Do 228 NG aircraft were ordered in 2017. These two aircraft will carry ''Seaspray 5000E'' AESA radar.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.janes.com/article/73801/leonardo-to-supply-aesa-radars-for-bangladesh-navy-s-new-dornier-228-multirole-aircraft| title=Leonardo to supply AESA radars for Bangladesh Navy\u2019s new Dornier 228 multirole aircraft| publisher=Janes| date=13 September 2017| accessdate=22 January 2017}}</ref> Bangladesh Navy also ordered two [[AgustaWestland AW159 Wildcat]] helicopters for anti-ship and anti-submarine roles. In April 2018, BN floated a tender for the procurement of two more similar helicopters.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://dgdp.gov.bd/dgdp/AP_TEN/s_doc/2247.pdf| title=TENDER SPECIFICATION OF HELICOPTERS| publisher=dgdp| accessdate=2 April 2018| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180403112457/http://dgdp.gov.bd/dgdp/AP_TEN/s_doc/2247.pdf| archive-date=3 April 2018| url-status=dead}}</ref> Government has a plan to induct more [[maritime patrol aircraft]], [[anti-submarine warfare]] [[helicopter]]s and [[maritime patrol aircraft|long range MPA]] in the near future.<ref name=\"pm\"/>\n\nBangladesh Navy attained three-dimensional capabilities with the induction of two refurbished [[Type 035G Submarine]]s on 12 March 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/politics/bangladesh-give-befitting-reply-if-attacked-pm-1374787|title=Bangladesh to give befitting reply if attacked: PM|work=[[The Daily Star (Bangladesh)|The Daily Star]]|date=12 March 2017 |accessdate=23 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dhakatribune.com/bangladesh/2017/03/12/bangladeshs-first-submarines-commissioned/|title=Submarines lead Bangladesh navy into new waters|work=The Dhaka Tribune|date=12 March 2017 |accessdate=23 March 2017}}</ref> These submarines are being used as training platforms for future submarine procurements.\n\n===Air Force===\nForces Goal 2030 plans to make the [[Bangladesh Air Force]] a technologically advanced, well-trained and well-equipped force that can deter any threat to the Bangladesh airspace. To efficiently perform the increasingly challenging duties and responsibilities, the air force is being divided into two separate commands: Southern air command and Northern air command.<ref name =\"expand\">{{cite web| url=http://www.m.mzamin.com/article.php?mzamin=72866| title=\u09ac\u09bf\u09ae\u09be\u09a8 \u09ac\u09be\u09b9\u09bf\u09a8\u09c0\u09a4\u09c7 \u0985\u09a4\u09cd\u09af\u09be\u09a7\u09c1\u09a8\u09bf\u0995 \u09b8\u09ae\u09b0\u09be\u09b8\u09cd\u09a4\u09cd\u09b0| publisher=The Daily Manab Zamin| date=7 July 2017|accessdate=13 November 2017}}</ref> Two airbases has already been set up - BAF base Sheikh Hasina at [[Cox's Bazar]]<ref>{{cite web| url=https://bdnews24.com/bangladesh/2011/04/03/pm-opens-air-force-base-in-cox-s-bazar| title=PM opens Air Force base in Cox's Bazar| publisher=Bdnews24.com| date=3 April 2011| accessdate=23 January 2018}}</ref> and BAF base Bangabandhu at Dhaka.<ref name=\"f7dt\">{{cite web| url=http://www.dhakatribune.com/bangladesh/2013/04/09/pm-opens-bangabandhu-air-force-base/| title=PM opens Bangabandhu Air Force Base| publisher=The Dhaka Tribune| date=9 April 2013| accessdate=23 January 2018}}</ref><ref  name=\"f7ds\">{{cite web| url=http://www.thedailystar.net/news/pm-launches-new-air-force-base| title=PM launches new air force base| publisher=The Daily Star| date=10 April 2013| accessdate=23 January 2018}}</ref> Two new air bases are under construction now, one at Barishal<ref name=\"expand\"/> and another at Sylhet.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://bdnews24.com/bangladesh/2017/12/31/hasina-announces-new-air-bases-to-strengthen-air-force| title=Hasina announces new air bases to strengthen air force| publisher=[[Bdnews24.com]]| date=31 December 2017| accessdate=1 January 2018}}</ref> A maritime air support operation centre (MASOC) will be set up under southern command.<ref name=\"expand\"/> The Air Force is on the process of setting up an advanced fighter pilot training unit named ''105 Advance Jet Training Unit'' which will be consist of three training squadrons that will provide advanced trainings to the fighter pilots trainees.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.theindependentbd.com/post/93542| title=Special training unit for BAF jet fighter pilots on the cards| publisher=The Independent| date=7 May 2017| accessdate=12 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Bangladesh Air Force procured 16 [[List of Chengdu J-7 variants#F-7BGI|Chengdu F-7BGI]] 3.5 generation fighter aircraft from China.<ref name=\"f7dt\"/><ref  name=\"f7ds\"/> process of procuring 4.5 generation [[multirole combat aircraft]] is going on. Bangladesh has signed a government to government contract with the United Kingdom for the supply of five off-the-shelf [[Lockheed Martin C-130J Super Hercules|C-130J]] aircraft served with the [[Royal Air Force]].<ref name=\"130j\">{{cite web| url=https://www.janes.com/article/90032/bangladesh-to-receive-five-surplus-uk-c-130j-airlifters-by-end-of-year| title=Bangladesh to receive five surplus UK C-130J airlifters by end of year| publisher=Janes 360| date=24 July 2019| accessdate=4 January 2020}}</ref> Already first aircraft has been delivered in August 2019.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.janes.com/article/90722/bangladesh-receives-first-of-five-uk-surplus-c-130j-transport-aircraft| title=Bangladesh receives first of five UK-surplus C-130J transport aircraft| publisher=Janes 360| date=28 August 2019| accessdate=4 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Bangladesh Air Force procured twenty one [[Mil Mi-17#Variants|Mil Mi-171Sh]] helicopters from Russia from 2010 to 2019 that can be used for both transport and attack roles.,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.security-risks.com/security-trends-south-asia/bangladesh/new-base-for-bangladesh-air-force-baf-1904.html|title=New Base for Bangladesh Air Force (BAF)|work=Security-risks.com|accessdate=27 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.itar-tass.com/economy/727823|title=Russia to deliver 5 transport combat helicopters to Bangladesh|work=TASS|accessdate=24 December 2014}}</ref> BAF also procured four [[AgustaWestland AW139]] helicopters from Italy for maritime SAR operations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newagebd.net/182186/self-confidence-to-take-nation-forward-pm/ |title=Self-confidence to take nation forward: PM |publisher=Newagebd.com |date=7 December 2015|accessdate=7 December 2015}}</ref> One [[Mil Mi-17#Variants|Mil Mi-171E]] helicopter was purchased for VIP transport role.\n\nFrom 2016, 23 new [[Nanchang CJ-6|PT-6]] [[Trainer (aircraft)#Basic training|Basic trainer]]s with [[glass cockpit]] were procured to replace the fleet of old PT-6.<ref name=\"expand\"/> BAF procured nine [[Hongdu JL-8|K-8]] [[Trainer (aircraft)#Advanced training|Advance jet trainer]]s to complement the fleet of seven [[Aero L-39 Albatros|L-39]]s.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://bdnews24.com/bangladesh/2014/09/27/bangladesh-air-force-inducts-new-chinese-fighters| title=Bangladesh Air Force inducts new Chinese fighters| publisher=Bdnews24.com| date=27 September 2014| accessdate=23 January 2018}}</ref> In 2015, BAF added three [[Let L-410 Turbolet]]s into a newly formed squadron of [[Trainer (aircraft)#Navigation trainers|Transport trainer]]s.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://unb.com.bd/pm-aircraft-lead| title=BD to build fighter planes one day, hopes PM| publisher=UNB| year=2015| accessdate=27 May 2015| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151228202214/http://unb.com.bd/pm-aircraft-lead| archive-date=28 December 2015| url-status=dead}}</ref> The Air Force also procured 16 [[Yakovlev Yak-130]] [[Trainer (aircraft)#Lead-in fighter training|Lead-in fighter trainer]] aircraft from Russia. Two [[AgustaWestland AW119 Koala]] helicopters have been procured to enhance helicopter training capabilities.\n\n[[File:Bangladesh Air Force FM90 Crotale SAM. (38169463025).jpg|220px|thumbnail|right|FM90 Crotale SAM of [[Bangladesh Air Force]].]]\nThe Air Force bought ''JH-16'', [[YLC-2 Radar|YLC-2]], [[YLC-6 Radar|YLC-6]] and ''JY-11B'' radar systems from China. A [[Selex RAT-31DL]] [[L Band]] [[Active electronically scanned array|AESA]] radar was also procured.<ref name=\"Italy_radar\">{{cite web|url = http://newagebd.net/248484/air-force-buy-long-range-radar-tk-1.47&nbsp;billion/ | title = Air force to buy long-range radar by Tk 147cr| publisher = newagebd.com | date = 26 August 2016 | accessdate = 8 September 2016 }}</ref>The radar arrived in 2018.<ref name=\"SIPRI\">{{cite web |url=http://armstrade.sipri.org/armstrade/page/trade_register.php |title=Trade-Register-1971-2018.rft |website=Stockholm International Peace Research Institute |access-date=2019-04-21}}</ref> In 2011, BAF inducted its first [[surface-to-air missile]] system, the [[HQ-7#HQ-7A .28FM-90.29|FM 90]], from China.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.thedailystar.net/news-detail-212914| title=Remain ever ready to protect sovereignty, PM asks air force| publisher=The Daily Star| date=5 December 2011| accessdate=23 January 2018}}</ref> Till date, two regiments of this system have been procured. In February 2017, BAF has floated a tender for the procurement of one battery of medium range surface to air missile (MRSAM) system consisting of one command vehicle, one search/target designation radar vehicle, one guidance radar vehicle and four missile firing vehicle. Each firing vehicle will have minimum four missiles.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://dgdp.gov.bd/dgdp/AP_TEN/s_doc/1019.pdf| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170220013236/https://dgdp.gov.bd/dgdp/AP_TEN/s_doc/1019.pdf| url-status=dead| archive-date=20 February 2017| title=Tender specification for the procurement of medium range surface to air missile (MSAM) system for BAF| publisher=dgdp| accessdate=19 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Bangladesh army selects Turkish Hisar-O air defence system|url=https://southasianmonitor.com/bangladesh/bangladesh-army-selects-turkish-hisar-o-air-defence-system/ |work=SOUTH ASIAN MONITOR|location=Bangladesh |date=9 August 2019 |access-date=6 September 2019 }}</ref>\n\nIn December 2017, Bangladesh Air Force floated a tender for the procurement of one Unmanned Aerial System (UAS). The system will consist of 3/4 [[Unmanned aerial vehicle|unmanned aerial vehicle (UAV)]] and [[Ground control station|ground control station (GCS)]]. The UAVs will have a range of 1000&nbsp;km and an endurance of 15 hours without weapon load and nine hours with weapon load. They will have 2/4 hardpoints with minimum payload requirement of 120&nbsp;kg.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://dgdp.gov.bd/dgdp/AP_TEN/s_doc/1926.pdf| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171222052742/https://dgdp.gov.bd/dgdp/AP_TEN/s_doc/1926.pdf| url-status=dead| archive-date=22 December 2017| title=Tender specification for the Unmanned Aerial Vehicle for Bangladesh Air Force| publisher=DGDP| date=| accessdate=19 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Procurement list==\n===Army===\n[[File:Bangladesh Army Nora B-52 SPG. (33563054062).jpg|220px|thumbnail|right|Bangladesh army uses Nora B-52K2 SPH]]\n* 44 [[Al-Khalid tank|MBT-2000]] [[Main battle tank]]s \n* 44 [[Type 15 tank|VT-5]] [[Light tank]]s\n* 18 [[Nora B-52|Nora B-52 K2]] [[Self propelled gun]]s\n* 72 [[Weishi Rockets#WS-22|WS-22A]] [[Multiple rocket launcher|MRLS]]{{citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n* 635 [[BTR-80]] [[Armoured Personnel Carrier|APC]]\n* 22 [[Otokar Cobra|Cobra I]] [[Infantry mobility vehicle|LAV]]\n* 50 [[Otokar Cobra|Cobra II]] [[MRAP]]\n* 10 [[BOV M11]] ARV\n* Two regiments of [[HQ-7#HQ-7A .28FM-90.29|FM 90]] short range [[Surface-to-air missile|SAM]]\n* [[QW-2 Vanguard 2|QW-2]] [[Man-portable air-defense system|MANPAD]]s\n* [[9K38 Igla#9K338 Igla-S (SA-24 Grinch)|Igla-s]] MANPADs\n[[File:Bangladesh Army METIS-M (23115643144).jpg|220px|thumbnail|right|Bangladesh Army 9K115-2 Metis-M]]\n* [[9K115-2 Metis-M|Metis-M]] [[Anti tank missile]]\n* [[PF-98]] ''Anti Tank Rocket''\n* [[SLC-2 Radar|SLC-2]] ''weapon locating radar''\n* Two [[Eurocopter AS365 Dauphin]] utility helicopters\n* Six [[Mil Mi-17#Variants|Mil Mi-171Sh]] combat helicopters\n* Four [[Diamond DA40]] training aircraft\n[[File:Bangladesh Army Aviation CN-295W.jpg|220px|thumbnail|right|Bangladesh Army Aviation Group EADS CASA C-295]]\n* One [[EADS CASA C-295|C-295W]] transport aircraft\n* 36 ''Bramor C4EYE'' battlefield reconnaissance UAV.\n* 100 Tri-Shark speed boats.\n\n===Navy===\n[[File:BNS Nirmul.jpg|220px|thumbnail|right|[[BNS Nirmul]], the second [[Durjoy-class LPC]] was commissioned in 2013.]]\n* Two [[Type 035G Submarine]]s (off-the-shelf)\n* Two [[Type 053H3 frigate]]s (off-the-shelf)\n* Two [[Type 053 frigate#Type 053H2 .28Jianghu-III.29 Ships of Class|Type 053H2 frigate]]s (off-the-shelf)\n* Two [[Hamilton class cutter]]s (off-the-shelf)\n* Four [[Type 056 corvette]]s\n* Two [[Castle-class patrol vessel|Castle-class corvette]]s (off-the-shelf)\n* Four [[Durjoy-class LPC]]s\n* Five [[Padma-class Patrol Vessel]]s\n* One [[HMS Roebuck (H130)|Roebuck class]] [[Survey vessel]] (off-the-shelf)\n* Six [[landing craft utility]]\n* Two [[landing craft tank]]\n* One ''Khan Jahan Ali Class'' oil tanker\n* Two [[Dornier Do 228|Dornier 228NG]] [[Maritime patrol aircraft|MPA]]\n* Two [[AgustaWestland AW109]] [[Search and rescue|SAR]] helicopters\n\n===Air Force===\n[[File:Bangladesh Air Force YAK-130 (17).png|220px|thumbnail|right|16 [[Yakovlev Yak-130]] already procured from Russia]]\n[[File:36100 Bangladesh Air Force MIG-29 Landing (8107450227).jpg|220px|thumbnail|right|BAF currently operates 8 MiG-29]]\n* 16 [[Chengdu J-7]] fighter aircraft\n* 5 [[Lockheed Martin C-130J Super Hercules|C-130J Super Hercules]] transport aircraft<ref name=\"130j\"/>\n* 16 [[Yakovlev Yak-130]] [[lead-in fighter trainer]]\n* 9 [[Hongdu JL-8|K-8]] [[Trainer (aircraft)#Advanced training|advance jet trainer]] aircraft\n* 3 [[Let L-410 Turbolet]] aircraft\n* 23 [[Nanchang CJ-6|PT-6]] [[Trainer (aircraft)#Basic training|basic trainer]]s<ref name=\"expand\"/>\n* 4 [[AgustaWestland AW139]] helicopters\n* 2 [[AgustaWestland AW119 Koala|AgustaWestland AW119 KX]] training helicopters\n* 21 [[Mil Mi-17]]1Sh helicopters\n* 1 [[Mil Mi-17#Variants|Mil Mi-171E]] helicopter\n* 2 regiment [[HQ-7#HQ-7A .28FM-90.29|FM 90]] short range [[Surface-to-air missile|SAM]] system\n* ''JH-16 Radar''\n* ''JY-11B'' Radar\n* [[YLC-2 Radar]]\n* [[YLC-6 Radar]]<ref>{{cite news |title = President inducts Air Defence Radar |url = http://www.theindependentbd.com/printversion/details/22714 |newspaper = The Independent |location = Dhaka |accessdate = 9 December 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Selex RAT-31DL]] Radar<ref name=\"Italy_radar\"/>\n\n==Structural and organizational developments==\n===Army===\n* Raising [[17th Infantry Division (Bangladesh)|17th Infantry Division]] at Sylhet\n* Raising [[10th Infantry Division (Bangladesh)|10th Infantry Division]] at Cox's Bazar\n* Raising [[7th Infantry Division (Bangladesh)|7th Infantry Division]] at Barishal\n* Formation of [[99th Composite Brigade (Bangladesh)|99th Composite Brigade]] near [[Padma Bridge]]\n* Formation of [[Para-Commando Brigade (Bangladesh)|Para-Commando Brigade]] and 2nd para-commando battalion\n\n===Navy===\n* Establishing submarine base, ''[[BNS Sheikh Hasina]]'' at pekua of Cox's Bazar\n* Establishing ''[[BNS Sher-e-Bangla]]'' the largest naval base of the country at Patuakhali\n* Establishment of naval base ''BNS Sheikh Mujib'' at Dhaka\n* Construction of ''BN fleet headquarters'' at the Sandwip channel of Chattogram\n* Formation of ''Naval Aviation Branch''\n* Formation of ''Submarine Branch''\n* Formation of naval special force [[Special Warfare Diving and Salvage|SWADS]]\n\n===Air Force===\n* Establishment of [[Air defense identification zone|ADIZ]] over Bangladesh airspace.\n* Establishment of ''BAF base Bangabanhu'' at Dhaka\n* Establishment of ''BAF base Sheikh Hasina'' at Cox's Bazar\n* Formation of ''105 Advance Jet Training Unit''\n\n==Indigenous defence industry==\n===[[Bangladesh Machine Tools Factory|BMTF]]===\n[[File:Bangladesh Army upgraded T-59G 'Durjoy' MBT. (27682919308).jpg|220px|thumbnail|right|''Type 59G Durjoy'' of [[Bangladesh Army]]]]\n* Upgradation of 174 [[Type 59 tank]]s to ''Type 59G Durjoy'' standard\n* Assembling ''Arunima Baliyaan'' trucks\n\n===[[Bangladesh Ordnance Factories|BOF]]===\n* Making and developing [[BD-08]] ''[[Assault Rifle]]'' and ''[[Light Machine Gun|LMG]]''<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.bof.gov.bd/site/page/29312da4-0a1e-41e0-95bf-5850b5c5d802/-| title=Small Arms Factory| publisher=Bangladesh Ordinance Factory| accessdate=30 December 2019}}</ref>\n* Making [[Type 80 machine gun|BD-14]] ''[[General-purpose machine gun]]''<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.bof.gov.bd/capabilities/| title=capabilities| publisher=Bangladesh Ordinance Factory| accessdate=6 May 2019| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190506172758/http://www.bof.gov.bd/capabilities/| archive-date=6 May 2019| url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* Making artillery shells of different calibers.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.bof.gov.bd/capabilities/| title=capabilities| publisher=Bangladesh Ordinance Factory| accessdate=6 May 2019| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190506172758/http://www.bof.gov.bd/capabilities/| archive-date=6 May 2019| url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* [[HG 85|Arges 84 BD Grenades]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.bof.gov.bd/site/page/1bd6a258-788d-421e-a5a8-dd92ae8b0ffa/-| title=High Calibre Ammunition Factory| publisher=Bangladesh Ordinance Factory| accessdate=30 December 2019}}</ref>\n* Assembling [[FN-6#FN-16|FN-16]] [[Man-portable air-defense system|MANPADS]].{{citation needed|date=September 2019}}\n\n===[[Khulna Shipyard]]===\n* Making [[Padma-class patrol vessel]]\n* Building [[Anti-submarine warfare|ASW]] capable [[Durjoy-class patrol craft]]s\n* Building [[survey vessel]]s<ref>{{cite news |author=Sayed Amar Khan |date=3 September 2019|title=Khulna Shipyard launches catamaran survey vessel for Bangladesh Navy |url=https://southasianmonitor.com/khulna-shipyard-launches-catamaran-survey-vessel-for-bangladesh-navy/ |work=South Asian Monitor |location=Bangladesh |access-date= 4 September 2019|}} </ref>\n\n===[[Chattogram Dry Dock Limited]]===\n* Construction of six 2000 ton Offshore Patrol Vessel (OPV).<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.cddl.gov.bd/file/notice/1579408834_OPV%20Notice.pdf| title=Tender notice| publisher=CDDL| date=16 January 2020| accessdate=22 January 2020}}</ref>\n* Construction of six frigates in collaboration with a foreign partner<ref name=\"pm\"/>\n\n===[[Bangabandhu Aeronautical Centre]]===\n* Indigenous [[Unmanned aerial vehicle|UAV]] development program.{{citation needed|date=September 2019}}\n* Training aircraft development program.{{citation needed|date=September 2019}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Coast Guard Goal 2030]]\n* [[Equipment of the Bangladesh Army]]\n* [[List of active aircraft of the Bangladesh Air Force]]\n* [[List of active ships of the Bangladesh Navy]]\n* [[List of active Bangladesh military aircraft]]\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Military of Bangladesh}}\n* [http://www.army.mil.bd/ Official Website of Bangladesh Army]\n* [http://www.baf.mil.bd/ Official Website of Bangladesh Air Force]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20141224170401/http://www.bangladeshnavy.org/ Bangladesh Navy]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Military of Bangladesh}}\n\n[[Category:Bangladesh Navy]]\n[[Category:Military acquisition]]\n[[Category:Military history of Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Military of Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Military reforms]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=April 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n\n[[File:\u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be\u09a6\u09c7\u09b6 \u09b8\u09be\u09ae\u09b0\u09bf\u0995 \u09ac\u09be\u09b9\u09bf\u09a8\u09c0\u09b0 \u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u09a4\u09c0\u0995.svg|200px|thumb|right|Emblem of Bangladesh Armed Forces]]\n'''Forces Goal 2030''' is the current long-term modernization program of the [[Bangladesh Armed Forces]] which began in 2009. The primary focus of the modernization program is to reform the military organization and training, expand the size of the forces, acquire modern weapons, and develop indigenous defense industries.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://thediplomat.com/2018/01/bangladeshs-ambitious-military-modernization-drive/|author=Shakil Bin Mushtaq|title=Bangladesh's Ambitious Military Modernization Drive|place=Bangladesh |date=2018-01-09|accessdate=2019-04-23}}</ref>\n\n==Plans and developments==\n===Army===\nForces Goal 2030 aims to make [[Bangladesh Army]] a well-trained, well-armed and technologically advanced force that can defend the country from any conventional and unconventional threats. The Bangladesh Army planned to conduct its activities under three independent corps \u2013 Central, Eastern and Western.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theindependentbd.com/printversion/details/32722|title=Army plans to work under three corps|last=Independent|first=The|access-date=28 August 2016}}</ref> Three new infantry divisions, the [[17th Infantry Division (Bangladesh)|17th infantry division]] at [[Sylhet District|Sylhet]],<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.dhakatribune.com/bangladesh/2013/sep/18/pm-launches-17-infantry-division| title=PM launches 17 Infantry Division| publisher=Dhaka Tribune| accessdate=21 September 2015}}</ref> [[10th Infantry Division (Bangladesh)|10th infantry division]] at Ramu in [[Cox's Bazar District|Cox's Bazar]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bssnews.net/newsDetails.php?cat=0&id=474604&date=2015-03-01 |title=PM urges army to remain prepared against any threat to democracy |publisher=Bangladesh Sangbad Sangstha |date= |accessdate=8 February 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161128184650/http://www.bssnews.net/newsDetails.php?cat=0&id=474604&date=2015-03-01 |archive-date=28 November 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and [[7th Infantry Division (Bangladesh)|7th infantry division]] at [[Barishal District|Barishal]]-[[Patuakhali District|Patuakhali]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dhakatribune.com/bangladesh/nation/2018/02/08/pm-reaches-patuakhali/|title=PM inaugurates Sheikh Hasina Cantonment in Patuakhali|publisher=Dhakatribune|date=8 February 2018|accessdate=8 February 2018}}</ref> have been raised to make the number of total infantry divisions ten. A Riverine Engineer Battalion is also going to be formed under a proposed cantonment at Mithamoine in Kishorganj.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.theindependentbd.com/home/printnews/104318| title=Army to get 97 more units in 4 years | publisher=The Independent| date=16 July 2017|accessdate=11 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.janes.com/article/72633/bangladesh-army-to-get-97-more-units-in-four-years-says-report| title=Bangladesh Army to get 97 more units in four years, says report| publisher=Jane's 360| date=26 July 2017|accessdate=11 August 2017}}</ref> A full-fledged cantonment is being established at [[Ruma Upazila|Ruma]] of [[Bandarban District]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.theindependentbd.com/arcprint/details/52702/2016-07-25|title=Focus on 1971 spirit, says PM|last=Independent|first=The|newspaper=Focus on 1971 spirit, says PM {{!}} theindependentbd.com|access-date=1 December 2016}}</ref> Government has a plan to add 97 new units within 2021. Of them, 19 units  will be formed for the Sylhet Cantonment, 22 for the Ramu Cantonment and 56 units for the Sheikh Hasina Cantonment in Lebukhali. Process of converting some regular infantry battalions into [[Paratrooper|para infantry]] battalions and [[mechanized infantry]] battalions is also going on.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bssnews.net/newsDetails.php?cat=0&id=742740&date=2018-05-13 |title=Stay alert to face internal & external threats |publisher=[[Bangladesh Sangbad Sangstha]] |date=13 May 2018 |accessdate=16 May 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180517152948/http://www.bssnews.net/newsDetails.php?cat=0&id=742740&date=2018-05-13 |archive-date=17 May 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> To increase special operation capabilities, ''2nd Commando Battalion'' has been raised. This battalion together with the ''1st Commando Battalion'' formed the sole [[Para-Commando Brigade (Bangladesh)|Para-Commando Brigade]] of the country.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.thedailystar.net/backpage/dhaka-cafe-attack-recounting-operation-thunderbolt-1427413| title=Recounting 'Operation Thunderbolt'| publisher=The Daily Star| date=3 July 2017| accessdate=11 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Bangladesh Army modular infantry. (30801511334).jpg|200px|thumb|right|New outfit of Bangladeshi infantry.]]\n\nSeveral steps has been taken to modernize the regular infantry outfits. The infantry soldiers are being equipped with modern gear like [[Night vision device|Night Vision Goggles (NVG)]], [[SPECTRA helmet|Ballistic helmets]], [[Ballistic eyewear|Eye protective gear]], [[Bulletproof vest]], person to person communicators, [[palmtop]] [[GPS navigation device|GPS device]] and [[Type 81 assault rifle|BD-08]] assault rifles with [[Collimator sight]]. To strengthen the mechanized infantry units, around 650 [[BTR-80]] APCs, 50 [[Otokar Cobra|Otokar Cobra I]] LAVs, 50 [[Otokar Cobra|Otokar Cobra II]] MRAPs and several [[BOV M11]] armoured reconnaissance vehicles have been added. To enhance the anti-tank capabilities, [[9K115-2 Metis-M|Metis-M]] missile systems, [[PF-98]] rocket systems and [[RPG-7|RPG-7V2]] [[Rocket-propelled grenade]]s were procured. Evaluation process of modern [[assault rifle]]s and [[submachine gun]]s is also going on.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://dgdp.gov.bd/dgdp/AP_TEN/notice/411.pdf|title=Evaluation of suitable small arms/assault riffle/sub-machine gun for Bangladesh Army| publisher=DGDP| accessdate=10 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe firepower of artillery units was increased by procuring [[Nora B-52|Nora B-52 K2]] self-propelled artillery systems. Four regiment of [[Weishi Rockets#WS-22|WS-22]] Guided Multiple Rocket Launcher System were also added. In 2019, army signed contract to procure one regiment of [[Kasirga rocket system|T-300 Kasirga]] MLRS system from Turkey.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.savunmahaber.com/en/brigadier-general-md-tariqul-alam-tariq-the-defence-attache-of-bangladesh-to-turkey-turkish-companies-are-winning-the-tenders-for-product-compatibility-lower-price-and-easy-after-sale-serv/|title=Brigadier General Md Tariqul Alam TARIQ, the Defence Attach\u00e9 of Bangladesh to Turkey: \"Turkish companies are winning the tenders for product compatibility, lower price and easy after sale service.\"| publisher=MSI Turkish Defence Review| date=31 March 2020|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref> [[SLC-2 Radar|SLC-2]] weapon locating radars were added to help the artillery firing. Procurement process of 155mm towed howitzer,<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.dgdp.gov.bd/dgdp/AP_TEN/notice/359.pdf| title=Evaluation of 155mm Howitzer| publisher=dgdp| date=24 September 2017| accessdate=24 November 2017}}</ref> 122&nbsp;mm field artillery howitzers<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.dgdp.gov.bd/dgdp/AP_TEN/notice/374.pdf| title=Evaluation of 122mm Howitzer| publisher=dgdp| date=21 November 2017| accessdate=24 November 2017}}</ref> and 105mm towed field artillery systems is going on.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.dgdp.gov.bd/dgdp/AP_TEN/notice/373.pdf| title=Procurement of 105mm howitzer| publisher=dgdp| date=| accessdate=25 November 2017}}</ref> Procurement of long range [[Multiple rocket launcher|multiple launch rocket system (MLRS)]] is also in the process.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://dgdp.gov.bd/dgdp/AP_TEN/notice/410.pdf|title=Evaluation of multiple launch rocket system Type A|publisher=DGDP|accessdate=10 April 2018}}</ref> To support accurate artillery firing, Bangladesh Army has procured 36 ''Bramor C4EYE'' battlefield reconnaissance UAV from Slovenia in 2017. These UAVs have a maximum range of 40 kilometres and endurance of 3 hours.\n\nThe Bangladesh Army procured 44 [[Al-Khalid tank|MBT-2000]] tanks from China in 2011. Army engineers have completed the upgradation process of [[Type 69/79 main battle tank|Type 69 tank]]s to ''Type 69IIG'' standard.<ref name=\"thedailystar\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/city/modernisation-army-continue-89149|title=Modernisation of army to continue|date=29 May 2015|work=The Daily Star|access-date=8 December 2017}}</ref> Upgradation of 174 [[Type 59 tank]]s to [[Type 59 tank#Foreign variants|Type 59G Durjoy]] standard is going on.<ref>{{cite news |date=28 May 2015 |title=Prime Minister Hasina expects greater involvement of army in development efforts |url=http://bdnews24.com/bangladesh/2015/05/28/prime-minister-hasina-expects-greater-involvement-of-army-in-development-efforts |newspaper=bdnews24.com}}</ref> Bangladesh Army has signed contract with China for 44 [[Type 15 tank|VT-5]] light tanks in 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eng.chinamil.com.cn/view/2019-12/20/content_9700539.htm|title=Bangladesh Navy receives two Chinese frigates|publisher=Chinamil|date=20 December 2019|accessdate=28 December 2019}}</ref> Army also started amphibious light procurement process in 2019.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://dgdp.gov.bd/dgdp/AP_TEN/notice/539.pdf| title=Standardization of light amphibious tank (tracked) and amph armoured repair and recovery vehicle (tracked) for Bangladesh Army| publisher=dgdp| date=23 April 2019| accessdate=30 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nTwo regiments of [[HQ-7#HQ-7A .28FM-90.29|FM 90C]] short range [[surface to air missile]] were added in 2016 to enhance air defence capabilities.<ref name=\"thedailystar\"/> In 2017, two [[Oerlikon GDF|Oerlikon GDF 009]] [[Anti-aircraft warfare|anti aircraft gun]] systems have been procured with Skyguard fire control radar.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://dgdp.gov.bd/dgdp/AP_TEN/s_doc/2615.pdf|title=TECHNICAL SPECIFICATION AND OTHER REQUIREMENTS FOR ITEM SER NO 1. CARTS HIGH EXPLOSIVE INCENDIARY (HEI) FOR RADAR CONTROL AIR DEFENCE GUN SYSTEM 35 MM OERLIKON GDF 009/SKYGURAD 3,QTY-1,000 NOS|publisher=DGDP|accessdate=3 September 2019}}</ref> In March 2018, a tender was floated for two local warning radars. The models shortlisted for the tender are [[Ground Master 400]] of [[Thales Group|Thales]], ''TRML 3D/32'' of [[Hensoldt]] and ''KRONOS Land'' of [[Leonardo S.p.A.|Leonardo]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dgdp.gov.bd/dgdp/AP_TEN/s_doc/2229.pdf|title=Tender specification of Local Warning Radar|publisher=DGDP|accessdate=24 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180324224420/http://dgdp.gov.bd/dgdp/AP_TEN/s_doc/2229.pdf|archive-date=24 March 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> In the same month, another tender was issued for procuring 181 [[Man-portable air-defense system]]s. Here, Chinese [[FN-6#FN-16|FN-16]], Russian [[9K38 Igla|Igla-S]] and Swedish [[RBS 70]] systems has been shortlisted.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://dgdp.gov.bd/dgdp/AP_TEN/a_doc/2192.pdf|title=Tender for surface to air missile|publisher=DGDP|accessdate=24 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Bangladesh Army LCT Shakti Shanchar (26749862156).jpg|200px|thumb|right|Bangladesh Army LCT Shakti Shanchar]]\n\nModernizing the army aviation wing is in full swing. Two [[Eurocopter AS365 Dauphin]]s were put into service in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.infodefensa.com/latam/2012/11/28/comunicado-eurocopter-as365-n3-dauphin-helicopters-enter-service-with-the-bangladesh-army-for-use-in-humanitarian-missions-and-vip-airlift.html|title=Eurocopter AS365 N3+ Dauphin helicopters enter service with the Bangladesh Army for use in humanitarian missions and VIP airlift.|publisher=infodefensa.com|date=|accessdate=29 May 2015}}</ref> Six [[Mil Mi-17#Variants|Mil Mi-171Sh]] helicopters were procured from Russia in 2016. One [[EADS CASA C-295|C-295]] transport aircraft was bought from Spain. Army Aviation has plan to add one more [[EADS CASA C-295]] transport aircraft and six more [[Mil Mi-17|Mil Mi-171Sh]] helicopters to its fleet soon. They also have a plan to add [[attack helicopter]]s to the fleet in the near future.<ref name =\"aagdev\">{{cite web| url=https://mzamin.com/article.php?mzamin=203653| title=\u09ae\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09be\u09a8\u09ae\u09be\u09b0\u0995\u09c7 \u09ac\u09b2\u09c7\u099b\u09bf \u09b0\u09cb\u09b9\u09bf\u0999\u09cd\u0997\u09be\u09a6\u09c7\u09b0 \u09ab\u09bf\u09b0\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09c7 \u09a8\u09c7\u09af\u09bc\u09be\u09b0 \u09b8\u09ac \u09ac\u09cd\u09af\u09ac\u09b8\u09cd\u09a5\u09be \u09a4\u09be\u09a6\u09c7\u09b0\u0995\u09c7 \u0995\u09b0\u09a4\u09c7 \u09b9\u09ac\u09c7 |language=bn | publisher=Daily Manab Zamin| date=13 December 2019| accessdate=14 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nTender was floated for procurement of a command ship in 2017. The vessel will be used as a floating command centre for different waterborne operations.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.dgdp.gov.bd/dgdp/AP_TEN/s_doc/997.pdf| title=Tender specification of vessel Type C (comd. vessel)| publisher=dgdp| accessdate=18 February 2017| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170219095610/http://www.dgdp.gov.bd/dgdp/AP_TEN/s_doc/997.pdf| archive-date=19 February 2017| url-status=dead}}</ref> Several tenders were floated to procure a total of six [[Landing craft tank]] for the army between 2017 and 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dailyasianage.com/news/71502/wms-to-build-two-combat-tank-carriers-for-army|title=WMS to build two combat tank carriers for Army|publisher=The Daily Asian Age|date=5 July 2017|accessdate=5 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170808075406/http://dailyasianage.com/news/71502/wms-to-build-two-combat-tank-carriers-for-army|archive-date=8 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.dgdp.gov.bd/dgdp/AP_TEN/s_doc/2089.pdf| title=Technical specification of vessel Type A| publisher=DGDP| accessdate=2 February 2018| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180203064247/http://www.dgdp.gov.bd/dgdp/AP_TEN/s_doc/2089.pdf| archive-date=3 February 2018| url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://dgdp.gov.bd/dgdp/AP_TEN/s_doc/2261.pdf| title=Technical specification of vessel Type A| publisher=DGDP| accessdate=23 April 2018| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180424072134/http://dgdp.gov.bd/dgdp/AP_TEN/s_doc/2261.pdf| archive-date=24 April 2018| url-status=dead}}</ref> Bangladesh army issued tender for procuring two ''Troops Carrier Vessel (TCV)'' in January 2018. The vessels will be able to carry 200 personnel.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://dgdp.gov.bd/dgdp/AP_TEN/s_doc/2082.pdf| title=Technical specification of vessel Type B| publisher=DGDP| accessdate=2 February 2018| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180202190531/http://dgdp.gov.bd/dgdp/AP_TEN/s_doc/2082.pdf| archive-date=2 February 2018| url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Navy===\nForces goal 2030 includes plan to  make the [[Bangladesh Navy]] a well-equipped three dimensional navy that can protect the maritime interests of Bangladesh. Modernization and expansion of the force is going on simultaneously. Bangladesh Navy is setting up a submarine base named [[BNS Sheikh Hasina]], at Pekua in [[Cox's Bazar]].<ref>{{cite news |date=12 October 2013 |title=Work started for land acquisition for submarine base: PM |url=http://primenews.com.bd/details/17340 |newspaper=Prime News |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140519185247/http://primenews.com.bd/details/17340 |archive-date=19 May 2014}}</ref> The largest naval base of the country is under construction at Rabanabad in [[Patuakhali]] named [[BNS Sher-e-Bangla]]. The base will have submarine berthing and aviation facilities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theindependentbd.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=233041:largest-naval-base-to-be-in-patuakhali-pm&catid=132:backpage&Itemid=122|title=Largest naval base to be in Patuakhali: PM|author=Shorwar Hossain|accessdate=24 December 2014}}</ref> A full-fledged operational base, named ''BNS Sheikh Mujib'', has been constructed in Khilkhet of Dhaka.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bssnews.net/?p=115568|title=PM commissions naval base \u2018BNS Sheikh Mujib\u2019|website=bssnews.net| accessdate=28 December 2019}}</ref> The construction works of a fleet headquarters at the Sandwip channel of Chattogram with ship berthing facilities is also going on.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://unb.com.bd/bangladesh-news/One-day-BD-Navy-to-become-builder-from-buyer-hopes-PM/59066|title=One day BD Navy to become builder from buyer, hopes PM|publisher=UNB|date=24 December 2017|accessdate=24 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171225035005/http://unb.com.bd/bangladesh-news/One-day-BD-Navy-to-become-builder-from-buyer-hopes-PM/59066|archive-date=25 December 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> Navy has taken initiative to make missiles and [[Identification friend or foe|IFF]] system in Bangladesh.<ref name=\"pm\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ispr.gov.bd/en/honourable-prime-minister-shiekh-hasina-reviewed-the-winter-president-parade-at-bangladesh-neval-academybns-chottagram/ |title=Honourable Prime Minister Shiekh Hasina Reviewed the Winter President Parade at Bangladesh Neval Academy(BNS), Chottagram |publisher=ISPR |date=22 December 2019 |accessdate=28 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nNavy's surface combatants are being increased with the induction of new and refurbished vessels. Two refurbished Chinese [[Type 053 frigate#Type 053H2 .28Jianghu-III.29 Ships of Class|Type 053H2 frigate]]s were bought and commissioned in 2014. The [[US Coast Guard]] provided two [[Hamilton class cutter|Hamilton class]] high endurance cutters, now serving as patrol and training frigates. Two Ex-[[Royal Navy]] [[Castle-class patrol vessel]]s were equipped with anti-ship missiles to serve as corvettes. To enhance surveying capacity, BN purchased an Ex-[[Royal Navy]] survey ship, commissioned as [[BNS Anushandhan]]. Navy has recently got the delivery of two refurbished [[ Type 053H3 frigate]]s which will be commissioned soon. Two more frigates of the same class has been ordered from the Chinese stock.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.janes.com/article/93346/china-hands-over-two-ex-plan-frigates-to-bangladeshi-navy| title=China hands over two ex-PLAN frigates to Bangladeshi Navy| publisher=Janes 360| date=20 December 2019| accessdate=26 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nTwo [[Type 056 corvette]]s were bought from China and commissioned in 2016. Two more corvettes of the same class have been delivered and awating commissioning.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2019-04/03/c_137947179.htm |title = CSIC builds two light frigates for Bangladesh |publisher = [[Xinhua News Agency|Xinhua]] |date= 3 April 2019 |accessdate = 4 April 2019}}</ref> Navy acquired two [[anti-surface warfare]] capable [[Durjoy-class LPC]]s in 2013 from China. Two more Durjoy class vessels with [[anti-submarine warfare]] capabilities were built at [[Khulna Shipyard]] and commissioned in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dhakatribune.com/bangladesh/2017/11/08/president-hamid-navy-ship-commissioning/| title=President Hamid commissions four new naval ships| publisher=The Dhaka Tribune|date= 8 November 2017| accessdate=9 November 2017}}</ref> [[Khulna Shipyard]] also built five [[Padma-class Patrol Vessel]]s which were commissioned in 2013. Currently, five more ships of the same class are under construction there. Khulna Shipyard is constructing two [[Research vessel|hydrographic research ships]] for the Bangladesh Navy. Two coastal survey vessels are under construction at [[Dockyard and Engineering Works Limited]]. Several [[Landing Craft Utility|LCU]]s and [[Landing craft tank|LCT]]s were also built at Khulna Shipyard and Dockyard and Engineering Works Limited. An oil tanker made by [[Ananda Shipyard and Shipways|Ananda Shipyard]] was commissioned in 2015. [[Chattogram Dry Dock Limited]] is in talks with different foreign shipbuilders for the constructing six frigates in collaboration with them.<ref name=\"pm\"/> The process is going on for procuring more [[corvette]]s, [[minesweeper]]s, oceanographic research ship and sail training ship is going on.<ref name=\"pm\"/>\n\n[[File:Dornier Do-228 MPA of Bangladesh Navy.jpg|200px|thumb|right|Dornier Do-228 MPA of Bangladesh Navy.]]\n\nThe Bangladesh Navy inaugurated its aviation wing with the induction of two [[AgustaWestland AW109]] helicopters in 2011. In 2013, two [[Dornier Do 228|Dornier Do 228 NG]] [[maritime patrol aircraft]] were added to the fleet. Two more Dornier Do 228 NG aircraft were ordered in 2017. These two aircraft will carry ''Seaspray 5000E'' AESA radar.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.janes.com/article/73801/leonardo-to-supply-aesa-radars-for-bangladesh-navy-s-new-dornier-228-multirole-aircraft| title=Leonardo to supply AESA radars for Bangladesh Navy\u2019s new Dornier 228 multirole aircraft| publisher=Janes| date=13 September 2017| accessdate=22 January 2017}}</ref> Bangladesh Navy also ordered two [[AgustaWestland AW159 Wildcat]] helicopters for anti-ship and anti-submarine roles. In April 2018, BN floated a tender for the procurement of two more similar helicopters.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://dgdp.gov.bd/dgdp/AP_TEN/s_doc/2247.pdf| title=TENDER SPECIFICATION OF HELICOPTERS| publisher=dgdp| accessdate=2 April 2018| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180403112457/http://dgdp.gov.bd/dgdp/AP_TEN/s_doc/2247.pdf| archive-date=3 April 2018| url-status=dead}}</ref> Government has a plan to induct more [[maritime patrol aircraft]], [[anti-submarine warfare]] [[helicopter]]s and [[maritime patrol aircraft|long range MPA]] in the near future.<ref name=\"pm\"/>\n\nBangladesh Navy attained three-dimensional capabilities with the induction of two refurbished [[Type 035G Submarine]]s on 12 March 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/politics/bangladesh-give-befitting-reply-if-attacked-pm-1374787|title=Bangladesh to give befitting reply if attacked: PM|work=[[The Daily Star (Bangladesh)|The Daily Star]]|date=12 March 2017 |accessdate=23 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dhakatribune.com/bangladesh/2017/03/12/bangladeshs-first-submarines-commissioned/|title=Submarines lead Bangladesh navy into new waters|work=The Dhaka Tribune|date=12 March 2017 |accessdate=23 March 2017}}</ref> These submarines are being used as training platforms for future submarine procurements.\n\n===Air Force===\nForces Goal 2030 plans to make the [[Bangladesh Air Force]] a technologically advanced, well-trained and well-equipped force that can deter any threat to the Bangladesh airspace. To efficiently perform the increasingly challenging duties and responsibilities, the air force is being divided into two separate commands: Southern air command and Northern air command.<ref name =\"expand\">{{cite web| url=http://www.m.mzamin.com/article.php?mzamin=72866| title=\u09ac\u09bf\u09ae\u09be\u09a8 \u09ac\u09be\u09b9\u09bf\u09a8\u09c0\u09a4\u09c7 \u0985\u09a4\u09cd\u09af\u09be\u09a7\u09c1\u09a8\u09bf\u0995 \u09b8\u09ae\u09b0\u09be\u09b8\u09cd\u09a4\u09cd\u09b0| publisher=The Daily Manab Zamin| date=7 July 2017|accessdate=13 November 2017}}</ref> Two airbases has already been set up - BAF base Sheikh Hasina at [[Cox's Bazar]]<ref>{{cite web| url=https://bdnews24.com/bangladesh/2011/04/03/pm-opens-air-force-base-in-cox-s-bazar| title=PM opens Air Force base in Cox's Bazar| publisher=Bdnews24.com| date=3 April 2011| accessdate=23 January 2018}}</ref> and BAF base Bangabandhu at Dhaka.<ref name=\"f7dt\">{{cite web| url=http://www.dhakatribune.com/bangladesh/2013/04/09/pm-opens-bangabandhu-air-force-base/| title=PM opens Bangabandhu Air Force Base| publisher=The Dhaka Tribune| date=9 April 2013| accessdate=23 January 2018}}</ref><ref  name=\"f7ds\">{{cite web| url=http://www.thedailystar.net/news/pm-launches-new-air-force-base| title=PM launches new air force base| publisher=The Daily Star| date=10 April 2013| accessdate=23 January 2018}}</ref> Two new air bases are under construction now, one at Barishal<ref name=\"expand\"/> and another at Sylhet.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://bdnews24.com/bangladesh/2017/12/31/hasina-announces-new-air-bases-to-strengthen-air-force| title=Hasina announces new air bases to strengthen air force| publisher=[[Bdnews24.com]]| date=31 December 2017| accessdate=1 January 2018}}</ref> A maritime air support operation centre (MASOC) will be set up under southern command.<ref name=\"expand\"/> The Air Force is on the process of setting up an advanced fighter pilot training unit named ''105 Advance Jet Training Unit'' which will be consist of three training squadrons that will provide advanced trainings to the fighter pilots trainees.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.theindependentbd.com/post/93542| title=Special training unit for BAF jet fighter pilots on the cards| publisher=The Independent| date=7 May 2017| accessdate=12 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Bangladesh Air Force procured 16 [[List of Chengdu J-7 variants#F-7BGI|Chengdu F-7BGI]] 3.5 generation fighter aircraft from China.<ref name=\"f7dt\"/><ref  name=\"f7ds\"/> process of procuring 4.5 generation [[multirole combat aircraft]] is going on. Bangladesh has signed a government to government contract with the United Kingdom for the supply of five off-the-shelf [[Lockheed Martin C-130J Super Hercules|C-130J]] aircraft served with the [[Royal Air Force]].<ref name=\"130j\">{{cite web| url=https://www.janes.com/article/90032/bangladesh-to-receive-five-surplus-uk-c-130j-airlifters-by-end-of-year| title=Bangladesh to receive five surplus UK C-130J airlifters by end of year| publisher=Janes 360| date=24 July 2019| accessdate=4 January 2020}}</ref> Already first aircraft has been delivered in August 2019.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.janes.com/article/90722/bangladesh-receives-first-of-five-uk-surplus-c-130j-transport-aircraft| title=Bangladesh receives first of five UK-surplus C-130J transport aircraft| publisher=Janes 360| date=28 August 2019| accessdate=4 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Bangladesh Air Force procured twenty one [[Mil Mi-17#Variants|Mil Mi-171Sh]] helicopters from Russia from 2010 to 2019 that can be used for both transport and attack roles.,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.security-risks.com/security-trends-south-asia/bangladesh/new-base-for-bangladesh-air-force-baf-1904.html|title=New Base for Bangladesh Air Force (BAF)|work=Security-risks.com|accessdate=27 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.itar-tass.com/economy/727823|title=Russia to deliver 5 transport combat helicopters to Bangladesh|work=TASS|accessdate=24 December 2014}}</ref> BAF also procured four [[AgustaWestland AW139]] helicopters from Italy for maritime SAR operations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newagebd.net/182186/self-confidence-to-take-nation-forward-pm/ |title=Self-confidence to take nation forward: PM |publisher=Newagebd.com |date=7 December 2015|accessdate=7 December 2015}}</ref> One [[Mil Mi-17#Variants|Mil Mi-171E]] helicopter was purchased for VIP transport role.\n\nFrom 2016, 23 new [[Nanchang CJ-6|PT-6]] [[Trainer (aircraft)#Basic training|Basic trainer]]s with [[glass cockpit]] were procured to replace the fleet of old PT-6.<ref name=\"expand\"/> BAF procured nine [[Hongdu JL-8|K-8]] [[Trainer (aircraft)#Advanced training|Advance jet trainer]]s to complement the fleet of seven [[Aero L-39 Albatros|L-39]]s.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://bdnews24.com/bangladesh/2014/09/27/bangladesh-air-force-inducts-new-chinese-fighters| title=Bangladesh Air Force inducts new Chinese fighters| publisher=Bdnews24.com| date=27 September 2014| accessdate=23 January 2018}}</ref> In 2015, BAF added three [[Let L-410 Turbolet]]s into a newly formed squadron of [[Trainer (aircraft)#Navigation trainers|Transport trainer]]s.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://unb.com.bd/pm-aircraft-lead| title=BD to build fighter planes one day, hopes PM| publisher=UNB| year=2015| accessdate=27 May 2015| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151228202214/http://unb.com.bd/pm-aircraft-lead| archive-date=28 December 2015| url-status=dead}}</ref> The Air Force also procured 16 [[Yakovlev Yak-130]] [[Trainer (aircraft)#Lead-in fighter training|Lead-in fighter trainer]] aircraft from Russia. Two [[AgustaWestland AW119 Koala]] helicopters have been procured to enhance helicopter training capabilities.\n\n[[File:Bangladesh Air Force FM90 Crotale SAM. (38169463025).jpg|220px|thumbnail|right|FM90 Crotale SAM of [[Bangladesh Air Force]].]]\nThe Air Force bought ''JH-16'', [[YLC-2 Radar|YLC-2]], [[YLC-6 Radar|YLC-6]] and ''JY-11B'' radar systems from China. A [[Selex RAT-31DL]] [[L Band]] [[Active electronically scanned array|AESA]] radar was also procured.<ref name=\"Italy_radar\">{{cite web|url = http://newagebd.net/248484/air-force-buy-long-range-radar-tk-1.47&nbsp;billion/ | title = Air force to buy long-range radar by Tk 147cr| publisher = newagebd.com | date = 26 August 2016 | accessdate = 8 September 2016 }}</ref>The radar arrived in 2018.<ref name=\"SIPRI\">{{cite web |url=http://armstrade.sipri.org/armstrade/page/trade_register.php |title=Trade-Register-1971-2018.rft |website=Stockholm International Peace Research Institute |access-date=2019-04-21}}</ref> In 2011, BAF inducted its first [[surface-to-air missile]] system, the [[HQ-7#HQ-7A .28FM-90.29|FM 90]], from China.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.thedailystar.net/news-detail-212914| title=Remain ever ready to protect sovereignty, PM asks air force| publisher=The Daily Star| date=5 December 2011| accessdate=23 January 2018}}</ref> Till date, two regiments of this system have been procured. In February 2017, BAF has floated a tender for the procurement of one battery of medium range surface to air missile (MRSAM) system consisting of one command vehicle, one search/target designation radar vehicle, one guidance radar vehicle and four missile firing vehicle. Each firing vehicle will have minimum four missiles.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://dgdp.gov.bd/dgdp/AP_TEN/s_doc/1019.pdf| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170220013236/https://dgdp.gov.bd/dgdp/AP_TEN/s_doc/1019.pdf| url-status=dead| archive-date=20 February 2017| title=Tender specification for the procurement of medium range surface to air missile (MSAM) system for BAF| publisher=dgdp| accessdate=19 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Bangladesh army selects Turkish Hisar-O air defence system|url=https://southasianmonitor.com/bangladesh/bangladesh-army-selects-turkish-hisar-o-air-defence-system/ |work=SOUTH ASIAN MONITOR|location=Bangladesh |date=9 August 2019 |access-date=6 September 2019 }}</ref>\n\nIn December 2017, Bangladesh Air Force floated a tender for the procurement of one Unmanned Aerial System (UAS). The system will consist of 3/4 [[Unmanned aerial vehicle|unmanned aerial vehicle (UAV)]] and [[Ground control station|ground control station (GCS)]]. The UAVs will have a range of 1000&nbsp;km and an endurance of 15 hours without weapon load and nine hours with weapon load. They will have 2/4 hardpoints with minimum payload requirement of 120&nbsp;kg.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://dgdp.gov.bd/dgdp/AP_TEN/s_doc/1926.pdf| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171222052742/https://dgdp.gov.bd/dgdp/AP_TEN/s_doc/1926.pdf| url-status=dead| archive-date=22 December 2017| title=Tender specification for the Unmanned Aerial Vehicle for Bangladesh Air Force| publisher=DGDP| date=| accessdate=19 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Procurement list==\n===Army===\n[[File:Bangladesh Army Nora B-52 SPG. (33563054062).jpg|220px|thumbnail|right|Bangladesh army uses Nora B-52K2 SPH]]\n* 44 [[Al-Khalid tank|MBT-2000]] [[Main battle tank]]s \n* 44 [[Type 15 tank|VT-5]] [[Light tank]]s\n* 18 [[Nora B-52|Nora B-52 K2]] [[Self propelled gun]]s\n* 72 [[Weishi Rockets#WS-22|WS-22A]] [[Multiple rocket launcher|MRLS]]{{citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n* 635 [[BTR-80]] [[Armoured Personnel Carrier|APC]]\n* 22 [[Otokar Cobra|Cobra I]] [[Infantry mobility vehicle|LAV]]\n* 50 [[Otokar Cobra|Cobra II]] [[MRAP]]\n* 10 [[BOV M11]] ARV\n* Two regiments of [[HQ-7#HQ-7A .28FM-90.29|FM 90]] short range [[Surface-to-air missile|SAM]]\n* [[QW-2 Vanguard 2|QW-2]] [[Man-portable air-defense system|MANPAD]]s\n* [[9K38 Igla#9K338 Igla-S (SA-24 Grinch)|Igla-s]] MANPADs\n[[File:Bangladesh Army METIS-M (23115643144).jpg|220px|thumbnail|right|Bangladesh Army 9K115-2 Metis-M]]\n* [[9K115-2 Metis-M|Metis-M]] [[Anti tank missile]]\n* [[PF-98]] ''Anti Tank Rocket''\n* [[SLC-2 Radar|SLC-2]] ''weapon locating radar''\n* Two [[Eurocopter AS365 Dauphin]] utility helicopters\n* Six [[Mil Mi-17#Variants|Mil Mi-171Sh]] combat helicopters\n* Four [[Diamond DA40]] training aircraft\n[[File:Bangladesh Army Aviation CN-295W.jpg|220px|thumbnail|right|Bangladesh Army Aviation Group EADS CASA C-295]]\n* One [[EADS CASA C-295|C-295W]] transport aircraft\n* 36 ''Bramor C4EYE'' battlefield reconnaissance UAV.\n* 100 Tri-Shark speed boats.\n\n===Navy===\n[[File:BNS Nirmul.jpg|220px|thumbnail|right|[[BNS Nirmul]], the second [[Durjoy-class LPC]] was commissioned in 2013.]]\n* Two [[Type 035G Submarine]]s (off-the-shelf)\n* Two [[Type 053H3 frigate]]s (off-the-shelf)\n* Two [[Type 053 frigate#Type 053H2 .28Jianghu-III.29 Ships of Class|Type 053H2 frigate]]s (off-the-shelf)\n* Two [[Hamilton class cutter]]s (off-the-shelf)\n* Four [[Type 056 corvette]]s\n* Two [[Castle-class patrol vessel|Castle-class corvette]]s (off-the-shelf)\n* Four [[Durjoy-class LPC]]s\n* Five [[Padma-class Patrol Vessel]]s\n* One [[HMS Roebuck (H130)|Roebuck class]] [[Survey vessel]] (off-the-shelf)\n* Six [[landing craft utility]]\n* Two [[landing craft tank]]\n* One ''Khan Jahan Ali Class'' oil tanker\n* Two [[Dornier Do 228|Dornier 228NG]] [[Maritime patrol aircraft|MPA]]\n* Two [[AgustaWestland AW109]] [[Search and rescue|SAR]] helicopters\n\n===Air Force===\n[[File:Bangladesh Air Force YAK-130 (17).png|220px|thumbnail|right|16 [[Yakovlev Yak-130]] already procured from Russia]]\n[[File:36100 Bangladesh Air Force MIG-29 Landing (8107450227).jpg|220px|thumbnail|right|BAF currently operates 8 MiG-29]]\n* 16 [[Chengdu J-7]] fighter aircraft\n* 5 [[Lockheed Martin C-130J Super Hercules|C-130J Super Hercules]] transport aircraft<ref name=\"130j\"/>\n* 16 [[Yakovlev Yak-130]] [[lead-in fighter trainer]]\n* 9 [[Hongdu JL-8|K-8]] [[Trainer (aircraft)#Advanced training|advance jet trainer]] aircraft\n* 3 [[Let L-410 Turbolet]] aircraft\n* 23 [[Nanchang CJ-6|PT-6]] [[Trainer (aircraft)#Basic training|basic trainer]]s<ref name=\"expand\"/>\n* 4 [[AgustaWestland AW139]] helicopters\n* 2 [[AgustaWestland AW119 Koala|AgustaWestland AW119 KX]] training helicopters\n* 21 [[Mil Mi-17]]1Sh helicopters\n* 1 [[Mil Mi-17#Variants|Mil Mi-171E]] helicopter\n* 2 regiment [[HQ-7#HQ-7A .28FM-90.29|FM 90]] short range [[Surface-to-air missile|SAM]] system\n* ''JH-16 Radar''\n* ''JY-11B'' Radar\n* [[YLC-2 Radar]]\n* [[YLC-6 Radar]]<ref>{{cite news |title = President inducts Air Defence Radar |url = http://www.theindependentbd.com/printversion/details/22714 |newspaper = The Independent |location = Dhaka |accessdate = 9 December 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Selex RAT-31DL]] Radar<ref name=\"Italy_radar\"/>\n\n==Structural and organizational developments==\n===Army===\n* Raising [[17th Infantry Division (Bangladesh)|17th Infantry Division]] at Sylhet\n* Raising [[10th Infantry Division (Bangladesh)|10th Infantry Division]] at Cox's Bazar\n* Raising [[7th Infantry Division (Bangladesh)|7th Infantry Division]] at Barishal\n* Formation of [[99th Composite Brigade (Bangladesh)|99th Composite Brigade]] near [[Padma Bridge]]\n* Formation of [[Para-Commando Brigade (Bangladesh)|Para-Commando Brigade]] and 2nd para-commando battalion\n\n===Navy===\n* Establishing submarine base, ''[[BNS Sheikh Hasina]]'' at pekua of Cox's Bazar\n* Establishing ''[[BNS Sher-e-Bangla]]'' the largest naval base of the country at Patuakhali\n* Establishment of naval base ''BNS Sheikh Mujib'' at Dhaka\n* Construction of ''BN fleet headquarters'' at the Sandwip channel of Chattogram\n* Formation of ''Naval Aviation Branch''\n* Formation of ''Submarine Branch''\n* Formation of naval special force [[Special Warfare Diving and Salvage|SWADS]]\n\n===Air Force===\n* Establishment of [[Air defense identification zone|ADIZ]] over Bangladesh airspace.\n* Establishment of ''BAF base Bangabanhu'' at Dhaka\n* Establishment of ''BAF base Sheikh Hasina'' at Cox's Bazar\n* Formation of ''105 Advance Jet Training Unit''\n\n==Indigenous defence industry==\n===[[Bangladesh Machine Tools Factory|BMTF]]===\n[[File:Bangladesh Army upgraded T-59G 'Durjoy' MBT. (27682919308).jpg|220px|thumbnail|right|''Type 59G Durjoy'' of [[Bangladesh Army]]]]\n* Upgradation of 174 [[Type 59 tank]]s to ''Type 59G Durjoy'' standard\n* Assembling ''Arunima Baliyaan'' trucks\n\n===[[Bangladesh Ordnance Factories|BOF]]===\n* Making and developing [[BD-08]] ''[[Assault Rifle]]'' and ''[[Light Machine Gun|LMG]]''<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.bof.gov.bd/site/page/29312da4-0a1e-41e0-95bf-5850b5c5d802/-| title=Small Arms Factory| publisher=Bangladesh Ordinance Factory| accessdate=30 December 2019}}</ref>\n* Making [[Type 80 machine gun|BD-14]] ''[[General-purpose machine gun]]''<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.bof.gov.bd/capabilities/| title=capabilities| publisher=Bangladesh Ordinance Factory| accessdate=6 May 2019| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190506172758/http://www.bof.gov.bd/capabilities/| archive-date=6 May 2019| url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* Making artillery shells of different calibers.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.bof.gov.bd/capabilities/| title=capabilities| publisher=Bangladesh Ordinance Factory| accessdate=6 May 2019| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190506172758/http://www.bof.gov.bd/capabilities/| archive-date=6 May 2019| url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* [[HG 85|Arges 84 BD Grenades]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.bof.gov.bd/site/page/1bd6a258-788d-421e-a5a8-dd92ae8b0ffa/-| title=High Calibre Ammunition Factory| publisher=Bangladesh Ordinance Factory| accessdate=30 December 2019}}</ref>\n* Assembling [[FN-6#FN-16|FN-16]] [[Man-portable air-defense system|MANPADS]].{{citation needed|date=September 2019}}\n\n===[[Khulna Shipyard]]===\n* Making [[Padma-class patrol vessel]]\n* Building [[Anti-submarine warfare|ASW]] capable [[Durjoy-class patrol craft]]s\n* Building [[survey vessel]]s<ref>{{cite news |author=Sayed Amar Khan |date=3 September 2019|title=Khulna Shipyard launches catamaran survey vessel for Bangladesh Navy |url=https://southasianmonitor.com/khulna-shipyard-launches-catamaran-survey-vessel-for-bangladesh-navy/ |work=South Asian Monitor |location=Bangladesh |access-date= 4 September 2019|}} </ref>\n\n===[[Chattogram Dry Dock Limited]]===\n* Construction of six 2000 ton Offshore Patrol Vessel (OPV).<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.cddl.gov.bd/file/notice/1579408834_OPV%20Notice.pdf| title=Tender notice| publisher=CDDL| date=16 January 2020| accessdate=22 January 2020}}</ref>\n* Construction of six frigates in collaboration with a foreign partner<ref name=\"pm\"/>\n\n===[[Bangabandhu Aeronautical Centre]]===\n* Indigenous [[Unmanned aerial vehicle|UAV]] development program.{{citation needed|date=September 2019}}\n* Training aircraft development program.{{citation needed|date=September 2019}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Coast Guard Goal 2030]]\n* [[Equipment of the Bangladesh Army]]\n* [[List of active aircraft of the Bangladesh Air Force]]\n* [[List of active ships of the Bangladesh Navy]]\n* [[List of active Bangladesh military aircraft]]\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Military of Bangladesh}}\n* [http://www.army.mil.bd/ Official Website of Bangladesh Army]\n* [http://www.baf.mil.bd/ Official Website of Bangladesh Air Force]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20141224170401/http://www.bangladeshnavy.org/ Bangladesh Navy]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Military of Bangladesh}}\n\n[[Category:Bangladesh Navy]]\n[[Category:Military acquisition]]\n[[Category:Military history of Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Military of Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Military reforms]]\n", "name_user": "AzfarShams", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eArmy:Added information.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Forces_Goal_2030"}
{"title_page": "Gail Lewis (academic)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date = July 2017}}\n\n{{Use British English|date=July 2017}}\n\n'''Dr Gail Lewis''' is a writer, psychotherapist, researcher, and activisit. She is currently Visiting Senior Fellow in the Department of Gender Studies at [[London School of Economics|the London School of Economics]],<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.lse.ac.uk/gender/people/visiting-scholars/Gail-Lewis.aspx|title=Gail Lewis|last=Science|first=London School of Economics and Political|website=London School of Economics and Political Science|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> and Reader Emerita of Psychosocial Studies at Birkbeck College.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.bbk.ac.uk/psychosocial/our-staff/visiting-staff/dr-gail-lewis|title=Dr Gail Lewis \u2014 Department of Psychosocial Studies, Birkbeck, University of London|website=www.bbk.ac.uk|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> She trained as a [[Psychotherapy|psychotherapist]] at the [[Tavistock and Portman NHS Foundation Trust|Tavistock Clinic]].<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\nLewis's work is rooted in [[Black feminism|black feminist]] and [[Anti-racism|anti-racist]] struggle, and a [[Socialism|socialist]], [[Anti-imperialism|anti-imperialist]] politics. She co-founded the Organisation for Women of African and Asian Descent ([[Organisation of Women of African and Asian Descent|OWAAD]]),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.londonreviewbookshop.co.uk/blog/2020/4/feminism-interrupted-a-conversation-with-lola-olufemi-and-momtaza-mehri|title=Feminism, Interrupted: A Conversation with Lola Olufemi and Momtaza Mehri {{!}} Blog|last=Bookshop|first=London Review|website=London Review Bookshop|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bl.uk/learning/histcitizen/sisterhood/clips/race-place-and-nation/civil-rights/143178.html|title=OWAAD|website=www.bl.uk|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> and she was a member of the [[Brixton Black Women's Group]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bl.uk/collection-items/gail-lewis-brixton-black-womens-group|title=Gail Lewis discusses Brixton Black Women's Group|website=The British Library|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> She has been a member of editorial collectives of the ''[[European Journal of Women's Studies]]'' and [[Feminist Review|''Feminist Review''.]] Lewis was interviewed for the oral history project 'Sisterhood and After: The Women's Liberation', archived at the [[British Library]], a project that interviewed \"feminists who were at the forefront of the Women\u2019s Liberation Movement in the 1970s and 80s\".<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bl.uk/sisterhood|title=Sisterhood and After: An Oral History of the Women's Liberation Movement|website=The British Library|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n== Biography and Education ==\nLewis studied Social Anthropology at the LSE, followed by an MPhil in Development Studies at the University of Sussex.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://radio.serpentinegalleries.org/contributors/gail-lewis/|title=Radio Serpentine - Gail Lewis|website=radio.serpentinegalleries.org|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> She passed her PhD in Social Policy with the Open University, and taught in the Open University Social Sciences Faculty between 1995-2004 and 2007-2013.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nLewis is an [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] fan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.opus.org.uk/conf18-keynote-gail-lewis/|title=CONF18 KEYNOTE: GAIL LEWIS {{!}} OPUS|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nLewis was Reader in Psychosocial Studies in the Department of Psychosocial Studies at [[Birkbeck, University of London|Birkbeck College]] until 2019, having joined the Department in 2013 and served as Assistant Dean between 2015 and 2017.<ref name=\":1\" /> She was Head of Department of the Institute of Women's Studies at Lancaster University.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ica.art/learning/hortense-spillers-conversation-gail-lewis|title=ICA {{!}} Hortense Spillers in conversation with Gail Lewis|website=www.ica.art|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\nShe has been a visiting Scholar at Clarke University, Massachusetts, USA.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nLewis frequently contributes to feminist discussions and events: she intereviewed [[Hortense Spillers]] for the [[Institute of Contemporary Arts|ICA]] in 2018.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tQ0ORQqSaWU|title=Gail Lewis and Hortense Spillers in conversation at the ICA, London.|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=2018|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nLewis has held many roles within academic publishing, including:\n\n* Co-Editor: European Journal of Women\u2019s Studies (2008 \u2013 2017)\n* Editorial Board: Social Politics (2007 \u2013 2010)\n* Editorial Board: Free Associations (2012 \u2013 2018)\n* Advisory Board: Studies in the Maternal (2010 \u2013 2017)\n* Co-Editor: Feminist Theory (2005 \u2013 07)\n* Editorial Collective: Feminist Review (1990 \u2013 1999)<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Scholarship ==\nPLACE scholar NAME described Lewis's scholarship as ..... \n\n== Activism and contributions to policy and politics ==\nIn 1998, Lewis assistend the legal team (led by solicitors Dieghton and Guedalla) representing Duwaynne Brooks (friend of Stephen Lawrence) in the MacPherson Inquiry into the Murder of Stephen Lawrence. With Professor S. Hall and Dr. E. McLaughlin, Lewis co-authored a submission on racial stereotyping.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nLewis gave evidence in 2000 to the 'Commission on the Future of Multi-Ethnic Britain', published as The Parekh Report.\u00a0Lewis identified the importance of gender to the future of multi-ethnic Britain and the role of social policy in social inclusion.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nWriting for the ''[[The Guardian|Guardian]]'' for a 2014 [[International Women's Day]] piece (which included feminist activitist [[Robin Morgan (journalist)|Robin Morgan]], [[Charlotte Raven]], Amrit Wilson, [[Selma James]], and [[Nawal El Saadawi]]), Lewis reflected on '[[intersectionality]]' and 'infighting' in [[feminism]], writing: \"The current debates about intersectionality recall, if not repeat, many of the battles fought between black and Asian feminists (along with their white anti-racist compa\u00f1eras) and white feminists who felt the struggle was being diverted by the call to pay attention to the inseparability of misogyny, racism, homophobia and class. While there remains much to do to expand an intersectional understanding of the conditions that determine what it means to be a woman and who may be included, without those earlier moments of infighting, feminism today would be all the poorer.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Morgan|first=Robin|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2014/mar/07/international-womens-day-defence-feminist-dissent-argued-priorities|title=International Women's Day: In defence of feminist dissent|date=2014-03-07|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-22|last2=Raven|first2=Charlotte|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|last3=Wilson|first3=Amrit|last4=James|first4=Selma|last5=Lewis|first5=Gail|last6=Saadawi|first6=Nawal El}}</ref>\n\n== Honours ==\n\n* In 2019, Lewis was invited to give the ''Feminist Review'' Annual Lecture. Lewis's lecture was entitled \u2018Lies and Disguises: The Racialisation of \u201cCulture\u201d and Child Sexual Exploitation\u2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://femrev.wordpress.com/2019/03/11/fr-annual-lecture-2019/|title=\u2018Lies and Disguises: The Racialisation of \u201cCulture\u201d and Child Sexual Exploitation\u2019 Gail Lewis {{!}} 21 March 2019, 5pm, SOAS, London|date=2019-03-11|website=feminist review|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n*Lewis holds an Honorary Doctorate from the Tavistock Clinic/Essex University.<ref name=\":0\" />\n* Lewis was recognised as one of the \"feminists who were at the forefront of the Women\u2019s Liberation Movement in the 1970s and 80s\", and interviewed for the oral history project 'Sisterhood and After: The Women's Liberation', archived at the [[British Library]].<ref name=\":3\" /> Other women interviewed for the project include [[Anna Davin]], [[Zoe Fairbairns]], and Barbara Taylor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bl.uk/sisterhood/interviews|title=Interviews with members of the Women's Liberation Movement|website=The British Library|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n== Selected publications ==\n\n=== Books ===\n\n* Editor and co-author of ''Citizenship: personal lives and social policy'' (Bristol: The Policy Press in Association with the Open University, 2004).\n* ''Race, Gender, Social Welfare: Encounters in a postcolonial society'' (Cambridge, Polity Press, 2000).\n\n=== Articles ===\n\n* \u2018Where Might we go if we Dare: moving beyond the \u201cthick, suffocating fog of whiteness\u201d\u2019, (2019) (in conversation with Clare Hemmings) Feminist Theory Vol. 20, Issue 4 pp1-17 <nowiki>https://doi.org/10.1177/1464700119871220</nowiki>\n* \u2018Questions of Presence\u2019, (2107) Feminist Review, 117, pp.1-19 <nowiki>https://doi.org/10.1057/s41305-017-0088-1</nowiki>\n* \u2018Of Becoming and Disturbance: one final offering, some thoughts on Familiar Stranger by Stuart Hall\u2019 (2017) Identities: Global Studies in Culture and Power\n* \u2018Not by Criticality Alone: contribution to a conversation with Sedgewick and Weigman\u2019, (2104) Feminist Theory, vol.15 (1), pp:31-38\n* \u2018Unsafe Travel: Experiencing Intersectionality and Feminist Displacements\u2019, (May 2013) Signs: a journal of women and culture,  DOI: 10.1086/669609, <nowiki>https://www.jstor.org/stable/10.1086/669609</nowiki> \n* \u2018In the Absence of Truth at Least not the Lie: travels towards self, other and relatedness\u2019, (2012) Psychology of Women Section Review (BPS), Spring\n* \u2018Where Might I Find You\u2019: Popular Music and the Internal Space of the Father\u2019, (2012) Psychoanalysis, Culture and Society\n* \u2018Locating the Complexities of Feminist Europe\u2019, (2012) European Journal of Women\u2019s Studies, 19 (2)\n* \u2018Our Memories of the Uprising: the 1980s revisited\u2019: report on a meeting,\u00a0 (2011) History Workshop Journal, Autumn (with Phillip Hatfield and Sarah Evans of the BL)\n* \u2018The \u2018Europe\u2019 of the European Journal of Women\u2019s Studies\u2019, (2010) European Journal of Women\u2019s Studies, 18 (1)\n* \u2018Celebrating Intersectionality? Debates on a Multi-Faceted Concept in Gender Studies', (2009) European Journal of Women\u2019s Studies, 16 (3)\n* \u2018Birthing Racial Difference: conversations with my mother and others\u2019 (2009); Studies in the Maternal, vol.1 (1), an e-journal, available at MaMSIE.bbk.ac.uk\n* \u2018Racialising Culture is Ordinary\u2019, (2007) Cultural Studies 21/6 (Nov), pp.866-886\n* \u2018Journeying Toward the Nation(al): Cultural Difference as the Impossibility of Citizenship\u2019, (2006) Mobilities, vol. 1(3) November\n* \u2018Imaginaries of Europe, Technologies of Gender, Economies of Power\u2019, (2006) European Journal of Women\u2019s Studies, 13(2), Spring, pp.87-102\n* \u2018Cosmopolitan Phantasies and Multicultural Publics\u2019, (2004) Treca special issue, Borders, Boundaries, Borderlands.\n* \u2018Welcome to the Margins: Diversity, Tolerance and Policies of Exclusion\u2019, (2005) Ethnic and Racial Studies, vol. 28, no.3 May special issue, pp.536-558.\n* \u2018Contemporary political contexts, changing terrains and revisited discourses\u2019, (2005) Ethnic and Racial Studies, 28, no.3, pp.423 \u2013 444.\n* \u2018Audre Lorde: Vignette and Mental Conversations\u2019, (2005), Feminist Review, 80, pp.130-145\n* \u2018Racialising emotional labour and emotionalising racialised labour:anger, fear and shame in social welfare\u2019, (2001) in Journal of Social Work Practice, vol.15, no.2, pp.125-142 (with Y. Gunaratnam)\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Birkbeck, University of London|Birkbeck]]\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date = July 2017}}\n\n{{Use British English|date=July 2017}}\n\n'''Dr Gail Lewis''' is a writer, psychotherapist, researcher, and activisit. She is currently Visiting Senior Fellow in the Department of Gender Studies at [[London School of Economics|the London School of Economics]],<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.lse.ac.uk/gender/people/visiting-scholars/Gail-Lewis.aspx|title=Gail Lewis|last=Science|first=London School of Economics and Political|website=London School of Economics and Political Science|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> and Reader Emerita of Psychosocial Studies at Birkbeck College.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.bbk.ac.uk/psychosocial/our-staff/visiting-staff/dr-gail-lewis|title=Dr Gail Lewis \u2014 Department of Psychosocial Studies, Birkbeck, University of London|website=www.bbk.ac.uk|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> She trained as a [[Psychotherapy|psychotherapist]] at the [[Tavistock and Portman NHS Foundation Trust|Tavistock Clinic]].<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\nLewis's work is rooted in [[Black feminism|black feminist]] and [[Anti-racism|anti-racist]] struggle, and a [[Socialism|socialist]], [[Anti-imperialism|anti-imperialist]] politics. She co-founded the Organisation for Women of African and Asian Descent ([[Organisation of Women of African and Asian Descent|OWAAD]]),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.londonreviewbookshop.co.uk/blog/2020/4/feminism-interrupted-a-conversation-with-lola-olufemi-and-momtaza-mehri|title=Feminism, Interrupted: A Conversation with Lola Olufemi and Momtaza Mehri {{!}} Blog|last=Bookshop|first=London Review|website=London Review Bookshop|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> and she was a member of the [[Brixton Black Women's Group]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bl.uk/collection-items/gail-lewis-brixton-black-womens-group|title=Gail Lewis discusses Brixton Black Women's Group|website=The British Library|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> She has been a member of editorial collectives of the ''[[European Journal of Women's Studies]]'' and [[Feminist Review|''Feminist Review''.]] Lewis was interviewed for the oral history project 'Sisterhood and After: The Women's Liberation', archived at the [[British Library]], a project that interviewed \"feminists who were at the forefront of the Women\u2019s Liberation Movement in the 1970s and 80s\".<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bl.uk/sisterhood|title=Sisterhood and After: An Oral History of the Women's Liberation Movement|website=The British Library|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n== Biography and Education ==\nLewis studied Social Anthropology at the LSE, followed by an MPhil in Development Studies at the University of Sussex.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://radio.serpentinegalleries.org/contributors/gail-lewis/|title=Radio Serpentine - Gail Lewis|website=radio.serpentinegalleries.org|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> She passed her PhD in Social Policy with the Open University, and taught in the Open University Social Sciences Faculty between 1995-2004 and 2007-2013.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nLewis is an [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] fan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.opus.org.uk/conf18-keynote-gail-lewis/|title=CONF18 KEYNOTE: GAIL LEWIS {{!}} OPUS|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nLewis was Reader in Psychosocial Studies in the Department of Psychosocial Studies at [[Birkbeck, University of London|Birkbeck College]] until 2019, having joined the Department in 2013 and served as Assistant Dean between 2015 and 2017.<ref name=\":1\" /> She was Head of Department of the Institute of Women's Studies at Lancaster University.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ica.art/learning/hortense-spillers-conversation-gail-lewis|title=ICA {{!}} Hortense Spillers in conversation with Gail Lewis|website=www.ica.art|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\nShe has been a visiting Scholar at Clarke University, Massachusetts, USA.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nLewis frequently contributes to feminist discussions and events: she intereviewed [[Hortense Spillers]] for the [[Institute of Contemporary Arts|ICA]] in 2018.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tQ0ORQqSaWU|title=Gail Lewis and Hortense Spillers in conversation at the ICA, London.|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=2018|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nLewis has held many roles within academic publishing, including:\n\n* Co-Editor: European Journal of Women\u2019s Studies (2008 \u2013 2017)\n* Editorial Board: Social Politics (2007 \u2013 2010)\n* Editorial Board: Free Associations (2012 \u2013 2018)\n* Advisory Board: Studies in the Maternal (2010 \u2013 2017)\n* Co-Editor: Feminist Theory (2005 \u2013 07)\n* Editorial Collective: Feminist Review (1990 \u2013 1999)<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Scholarship ==\nPLACE scholar NAME described Lewis's scholarship as ..... \n\n== Activism and contributions to policy and politics ==\nIn 1998, Lewis assistend the legal team (led by solicitors Dieghton and Guedalla) representing Duwaynne Brooks (friend of Stephen Lawrence) in the MacPherson Inquiry into the Murder of Stephen Lawrence. With Professor S. Hall and Dr. E. McLaughlin, Lewis co-authored a submission on racial stereotyping.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nLewis gave evidence in 2000 to the 'Commission on the Future of Multi-Ethnic Britain', published as The Parekh Report.\u00a0Lewis identified the importance of gender to the future of multi-ethnic Britain and the role of social policy in social inclusion.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nWriting for the ''[[The Guardian|Guardian]]'' for a 2014 [[International Women's Day]] piece (which included feminist activitist [[Robin Morgan (journalist)|Robin Morgan]], [[Charlotte Raven]], Amrit Wilson, [[Selma James]], and [[Nawal El Saadawi]]), Lewis reflected on '[[intersectionality]]' and 'infighting' in [[feminism]], writing: \"The current debates about intersectionality recall, if not repeat, many of the battles fought between black and Asian feminists (along with their white anti-racist compa\u00f1eras) and white feminists who felt the struggle was being diverted by the call to pay attention to the inseparability of misogyny, racism, homophobia and class. While there remains much to do to expand an intersectional understanding of the conditions that determine what it means to be a woman and who may be included, without those earlier moments of infighting, feminism today would be all the poorer.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Morgan|first=Robin|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2014/mar/07/international-womens-day-defence-feminist-dissent-argued-priorities|title=International Women's Day: In defence of feminist dissent|date=2014-03-07|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-22|last2=Raven|first2=Charlotte|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|last3=Wilson|first3=Amrit|last4=James|first4=Selma|last5=Lewis|first5=Gail|last6=Saadawi|first6=Nawal El}}</ref>\n\n== Honours ==\n\n* In 2019, Lewis was invited to give the ''Feminist Review'' Annual Lecture. Lewis's lecture was entitled \u2018Lies and Disguises: The Racialisation of \u201cCulture\u201d and Child Sexual Exploitation\u2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://femrev.wordpress.com/2019/03/11/fr-annual-lecture-2019/|title=\u2018Lies and Disguises: The Racialisation of \u201cCulture\u201d and Child Sexual Exploitation\u2019 Gail Lewis {{!}} 21 March 2019, 5pm, SOAS, London|date=2019-03-11|website=feminist review|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n*Lewis holds an Honorary Doctorate from the Tavistock Clinic/Essex University.<ref name=\":0\" />\n* Lewis was recognised as one of the \"feminists who were at the forefront of the Women\u2019s Liberation Movement in the 1970s and 80s\", and interviewed for the oral history project 'Sisterhood and After: The Women's Liberation', archived at the [[British Library]].<ref name=\":3\" /> Other women interviewed for the project include [[Anna Davin]], [[Zoe Fairbairns]], and Barbara Taylor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bl.uk/sisterhood/interviews|title=Interviews with members of the Women's Liberation Movement|website=The British Library|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n== Selected publications ==\n\n=== Books ===\n\n* Editor and co-author of ''Citizenship: personal lives and social policy'' (Bristol: The Policy Press in Association with the Open University, 2004).\n* ''Race, Gender, Social Welfare: Encounters in a postcolonial society'' (Cambridge, Polity Press, 2000).\n\n=== Articles ===\n\n* \u2018Where Might we go if we Dare: moving beyond the \u201cthick, suffocating fog of whiteness\u201d\u2019, (2019) (in conversation with Clare Hemmings) Feminist Theory Vol. 20, Issue 4 pp1-17 <nowiki>https://doi.org/10.1177/1464700119871220</nowiki>\n* \u2018Questions of Presence\u2019, (2107) Feminist Review, 117, pp.1-19 <nowiki>https://doi.org/10.1057/s41305-017-0088-1</nowiki>\n* \u2018Of Becoming and Disturbance: one final offering, some thoughts on Familiar Stranger by Stuart Hall\u2019 (2017) Identities: Global Studies in Culture and Power\n* \u2018Not by Criticality Alone: contribution to a conversation with Sedgewick and Weigman\u2019, (2104) Feminist Theory, vol.15 (1), pp:31-38\n* \u2018Unsafe Travel: Experiencing Intersectionality and Feminist Displacements\u2019, (May 2013) Signs: a journal of women and culture,  DOI: 10.1086/669609, <nowiki>https://www.jstor.org/stable/10.1086/669609</nowiki> \n* \u2018In the Absence of Truth at Least not the Lie: travels towards self, other and relatedness\u2019, (2012) Psychology of Women Section Review (BPS), Spring\n* \u2018Where Might I Find You\u2019: Popular Music and the Internal Space of the Father\u2019, (2012) Psychoanalysis, Culture and Society\n* \u2018Locating the Complexities of Feminist Europe\u2019, (2012) European Journal of Women\u2019s Studies, 19 (2)\n* \u2018Our Memories of the Uprising: the 1980s revisited\u2019: report on a meeting,\u00a0 (2011) History Workshop Journal, Autumn (with Phillip Hatfield and Sarah Evans of the BL)\n* \u2018The \u2018Europe\u2019 of the European Journal of Women\u2019s Studies\u2019, (2010) European Journal of Women\u2019s Studies, 18 (1)\n* \u2018Celebrating Intersectionality? Debates on a Multi-Faceted Concept in Gender Studies', (2009) European Journal of Women\u2019s Studies, 16 (3)\n* \u2018Birthing Racial Difference: conversations with my mother and others\u2019 (2009); Studies in the Maternal, vol.1 (1), an e-journal, available at MaMSIE.bbk.ac.uk\n* \u2018Racialising Culture is Ordinary\u2019, (2007) Cultural Studies 21/6 (Nov), pp.866-886\n* \u2018Journeying Toward the Nation(al): Cultural Difference as the Impossibility of Citizenship\u2019, (2006) Mobilities, vol. 1(3) November\n* \u2018Imaginaries of Europe, Technologies of Gender, Economies of Power\u2019, (2006) European Journal of Women\u2019s Studies, 13(2), Spring, pp.87-102\n* \u2018Cosmopolitan Phantasies and Multicultural Publics\u2019, (2004) Treca special issue, Borders, Boundaries, Borderlands.\n* \u2018Welcome to the Margins: Diversity, Tolerance and Policies of Exclusion\u2019, (2005) Ethnic and Racial Studies, vol. 28, no.3 May special issue, pp.536-558.\n* \u2018Contemporary political contexts, changing terrains and revisited discourses\u2019, (2005) Ethnic and Racial Studies, 28, no.3, pp.423 \u2013 444.\n* \u2018Audre Lorde: Vignette and Mental Conversations\u2019, (2005), Feminist Review, 80, pp.130-145\n* \u2018Racialising emotional labour and emotionalising racialised labour:anger, fear and shame in social welfare\u2019, (2001) in Journal of Social Work Practice, vol.15, no.2, pp.125-142 (with Y. Gunaratnam)\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Birkbeck, University of London|Birkbeck]]\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n", "name_user": "Medievalfran", "label": "safe", "comment": "Additional OWAAD citation.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gail_Lewis_(academic)"}
{"title_page": "The Parent Trap (film series)", "text_new": "{{italic title}}\n'''''The Parent Trap''''' is a [[film series]] produced by [[Walt Disney Pictures]], originating in 1961 with [[Hayley Mills]]. She played both roles of [[The Twins (The Parent Trap)|twin sisters]] who were raised separately by divorced parents, without any knowledge of each other. They meet at a summer holiday camp, and switch places so that they can each meet their other parent. Mills reprised her roles three times in subsequent [[Television film|made-for-television]] sequels. \n\nA [[The Parent Trap (1998 film)|remake]] was released in 1998, with a plot similar to the original film and written by the original film's writer/director [[David Swift (director)|David Swift]], with segments of the story being reworked into a [[Romance film|romantic]]-[[Comedy film|comedy]]. The twins were portrayed by [[Lindsay Lohan]].\n\n==Films==\n===''The Parent Trap'' (1961)===\n{{Main|The Parent Trap (1961 film)}}\n''The Parent Trap'' was written and directed by [[David Swift (director)|David Swift]] for [[Walt Disney Pictures]] released in 1961. It was based on the book ''[[Lottie and Lisa|Das Doppelte Lottchen]]'' written by [[Erich K\u00e4stner]]. The film stars [[Hayley Mills]] who plays the roles of the thirteen-year-old twin girls, Sharon and Susan. [[Maureen O'Hara]] and [[Brian Keith]] play the twins\u2019 parents, Maggie and Mitch. The film is about the two girls who meet at a summer camp as strangers and realize that they are identical twins. They switch places so that each can meet the other parent, and they plan to bring their divorced parents back together. Soon after switching, the twins learn that there is a new woman, named Vicky Robinson (played by [[Joanna Barnes]]), in their father's life. After Mitch tells Sharon about his engagement to Vicky, the girls come up with a new game plan to get rid of the woman who threatens their plan to reconnect their parents.<ref>''The Parent Trap.'' Dir. David Swift. Perf. Hayley Mills, Maureen O\u2019Hara, and Brian Keith. Walt Disney, 1961. Film.</ref>\n\n===''The Parent Trap II'' (1986)===\n{{Main|The Parent Trap II}}\n''The Parent Trap II'', written by Stuart Krieger, is a made-for-television film that aired on July 26, 1986 on the [[Disney Channel]]. It was directed by [[Ronald F. Maxwell]]. The film is a continuation of the Walt Disney film ''The Parent Trap''. ''The Parent Trap II'' was filmed twenty-five years after the original film. The idea of a second film was announced in 1985. The only actor who returned from the original film, Hayley Mills, continues to portray the twins, Sharon and Susan. ''The Parent Trap II'' focuses on Sharon's daughter Nikki who tries to set up her mother with her best friend's father, portrayed by [[Tom Skerritt]]. All the music was composed by [[Charles Fox (composer)|Charles Fox]] as well as the title song \"Lets Keep What We Got\" was performed by [[Marilyn McCoo]].\n\n===''Parent Trap III'' (1989)===\n\n{{Main|Parent Trap III}}\n''The Parent Trap II'' was such a success for the Disney Channel that it spawned another made-for-television sequel, ''Parent Trap III'', in 1989. Hayley Mills again reprises her roles as twins Sharon and Susan, with [[Barry Bostwick]] as a father of triplet girls and [[Patricia Richardson]] as his snobbish girlfriend.\n\n===''Parent Trap: Hawaiian Honeymoon'' (1989)===\n{{Main|Parent Trap: Hawaiian Honeymoon}}\n''Parent Trap: Hawaiian Honeymoon'' (1989) is the final made-for-television sequel, with Hayley Mills again reprising her roles as Sharon and Susan, now both remarried. Also returning from ''Parent Trap III'' is Barry Bostwick and the Creel triplets: Joy, [[Leanna Creel|Leanna]] and [[Monica Lacy|Monica]].\n\n===''The Parent Trap'' (1998)===\n\n{{Main|The Parent Trap (1998 film)}}\n[[Lindsay Lohan]] stars in the remake of the original ''Parent Trap'' film, playing the role of the identical twins whose lives change at the summer camp they attend. The remake caught the attention of audiences when it premiered on July 29, 1998. The parents of the twins, Nick Parker (played by [[Dennis Quaid]]) and Elizabeth James (played by [[Natasha Richardson]]), marry on a cruise ship and quickly figure out their lives are in two separate places. They each take one of the twins and then go their separate ways. Eleven years pass and the identical twins, Annie James and Hallie Parker, embark on their summer journeys not knowing each other. The initial rivalry between them turns out to bring them closer and they realize that they must be sisters. Their new goal is to make their parents fall in love again before their father and his fianc\u00e9 Meredeth Blake (played by [[Elaine Hendrix]]) marry. The film was directed by [[Nancy Meyers]].\n\n===Potential remake===\nOn February 8, 2018, ''The Hollywood Reporter'' revealed that remakes of several live-action films are in development as exclusive content for [[The Walt Disney Company|Walt Disney Studios]]' upcoming streaming service [[Disney+]]; with one of those named in the announcement being ''The Parent Trap''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/disney-planning-muppets-reboot-streaming-service-1086800 |title=Disney Planning Another 'Muppets' Reboot for Its Streaming Service (Exclusive) |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=February 21, 2018 |accessdate=February 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Documentary on the film series==\n\n\nFamily Films Productions is developing ''The Legacy of The Parent Trap'', a documentary film that gives a retrospective insight into developing ''The Parent Trap''. <ref>http://www.familyfilmsproductions.com</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hWzPemw75M8|title=The Legacy of The Parent Trap - Official Film Trailer |first=|last=FamilyFilmsProductions.com|date=23 June 2018|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref> The film will reportedly feature memories and stories of various cast and crew, about the original 1961 film and its three sequels. Among the interviews, all-new footage featuring Hayley Mills will be included. Additional interviewees include Tom Skerritt, Carrie Kei Heim, Creel triplets including, Monica Creel Lacy, Leanna & Joy Creel, Susan Henning, Ron Maxwell (Director of ''Parent Trap II'', Mollie Miller (Director of ''Parent Trap III''/''Hawaiian Honeymoon''), Tommy Sands, and Joanna Barnes and even Lynette Winters, and Kay Cole (camp inch scenes). [[Bridgette Andersen]]'s Teresa mother discusses reflections on experiences that occurred on-set during filming of ''The Parent Trap II'', with director Ron Maxwell, among others. Marilyn McCoo also is featured sharing memories about recording music for ''Parent Trap II''. Charles Fox who wrote the theme, \"Let's Get What We Got\" that was the title music in the opening for \"The Parent Trap II\", and the entire music score. He is also featured on-camera, with talking about his experiences in the music.  \n\nThe project will analyze and also focus on the life of Erich Kastner who wrote the original German book, ''[[Lottie and Lisa|Das Doppelte Lottchen]]''  that the films were based on. Luke Springman, German professor Aaron Pacentine will executive produce the film. This is the first full-length film documentary that details coverage on the 1980s Parent Trap films, and the first time the director, Mollie Miller, has spoken out publicly about the original film since then.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Lottie and Lisa}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Parent Trap (film series), The}}\n[[Category:Comedy film series]]\n[[Category:The Parent Trap films| ]]\n[[Category:Children's film series]]\n[[Category:Films about sisters]]\n[[Category:Disney film series]]\n", "text_old": "{{italic title}}\n'''''The Parent Trap''''' is a [[film series]] produced by [[Walt Disney Pictures]], originating in 1961 with [[Hayley Mills]]. She played both roles of [[The Twins (The Parent Trap)|twin sisters]] who were raised separately by divorced parents, without any knowledge of each other. They meet at a summer holiday camp, and switch places so that they can each meet their other parent. Mills reprised her roles three times in subsequent [[Television film|made-for-television]] sequels. \n\nA [[The Parent Trap (1998 film)|remake]] was released in 1998, with a plot similar to the original film and written by the original film's writer/director [[David Swift (director)|David Swift]], with segments of the story being reworked into a [[Romance film|romantic]]-[[Comedy film|comedy]]. The twins were portrayed by [[Lindsay Lohan]].\n\n==Films==\n===''The Parent Trap'' (1961)===\n{{Main|The Parent Trap (1961 film)}}\n''The Parent Trap'' was written and directed by [[David Swift (director)|David Swift]] for [[Walt Disney Pictures]] released in 1961. It was based on the book ''[[Lottie and Lisa|Das Doppelte Lottchen]]'' written by [[Erich K\u00e4stner]]. The film stars [[Hayley Mills]] who plays the roles of the thirteen-year-old twin girls, Sharon and Susan. [[Maureen O'Hara]] and [[Brian Keith]] play the twins\u2019 parents, Maggie and Mitch. The film is about the two girls who meet at a summer camp as strangers and realize that they are identical twins. They switch places so that each can meet the other parent, and they plan to bring their divorced parents back together. Soon after switching, the twins learn that there is a new woman, named Vicky Robinson (played by [[Joanna Barnes]]), in their father's life. After Mitch tells Sharon about his engagement to Vicky, the girls come up with a new game plan to get rid of the woman who threatens their plan to reconnect their parents.<ref>''The Parent Trap.'' Dir. David Swift. Perf. Hayley Mills, Maureen O\u2019Hara, and Brian Keith. Walt Disney, 1961. Film.</ref>\n\n===''The Parent Trap II'' (1986)===\n{{Main|The Parent Trap II}}\n''The Parent Trap II'', written by Stuart Krieger, is a made-for-television film that aired on July 26, 1986 on the [[Disney Channel]]. It was directed by [[Ronald F. Maxwell]]. The film is a continuation of the Walt Disney film ''The Parent Trap''. ''The Parent Trap II'' was filmed twenty-five years after the original film. The idea of a second film was announced in 1985. The only actor who returned from the original film, Hayley Mills, continues to portray the twins, Sharon and Susan. ''The Parent Trap II'' focuses on Sharon's daughter Nikki who tries to set up her mother with her best friend's father, portrayed by [[Tom Skerritt]]. All the music was composed by [[Charles Fox (composer)|Charles Fox]] as well as the title song \"Lets Keep What We Got\" was performed by [[Marilyn McCoo]].\n\n===''Parent Trap III'' (1989)===\n\n{{Main|Parent Trap III}}\n''The Parent Trap II'' was such a success for the Disney Channel that it spawned another made-for-television sequel, ''Parent Trap III'', in 1989. Hayley Mills again reprises her roles as twins Sharon and Susan, with [[Barry Bostwick]] as a father of triplet girls and [[Patricia Richardson]] as his snobbish girlfriend.\n\n===''Parent Trap: Hawaiian Honeymoon'' (1989)===\n{{Main|Parent Trap: Hawaiian Honeymoon}}\n''Parent Trap: Hawaiian Honeymoon'' (1989) is the final made-for-television sequel, with Hayley Mills again reprising her roles as Sharon and Susan, now both married. Also returning from ''Parent Trap III'' is Barry Bostwick and the Creel triplets: Joy, [[Leanna Creel|Leanna]] and [[Monica Lacy|Monica]].\n\n===''The Parent Trap'' (1998)===\n\n{{Main|The Parent Trap (1998 film)}}\n[[Lindsay Lohan]] stars in the remake of the original ''Parent Trap'' film, playing the role of the identical twins whose lives change at the summer camp they attend. The remake caught the attention of audiences when it premiered on July 29, 1998. The parents of the twins, Nick Parker (played by [[Dennis Quaid]]) and Elizabeth James (played by [[Natasha Richardson]]), marry on a cruise ship and quickly figure out their lives are in two separate places. They each take one of the twins and then go their separate ways. Eleven years pass and the identical twins, Annie James and Hallie Parker, embark on their summer journeys not knowing each other. The initial rivalry between them turns out to bring them closer and they realize that they must be sisters. Their new goal is to make their parents fall in love again before their father and his fianc\u00e9 Meredeth Blake (played by [[Elaine Hendrix]]) marry. The film was directed by [[Nancy Meyers]].\n\n===Potential remake===\nOn February 8, 2018, ''The Hollywood Reporter'' revealed that remakes of several live-action films are in development as exclusive content for [[The Walt Disney Company|Walt Disney Studios]]' upcoming streaming service [[Disney+]]; with one of those named in the announcement being ''The Parent Trap''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/disney-planning-muppets-reboot-streaming-service-1086800 |title=Disney Planning Another 'Muppets' Reboot for Its Streaming Service (Exclusive) |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=February 21, 2018 |accessdate=February 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Documentary on the film series==\n\n\nFamily Films Productions is developing ''The Legacy of The Parent Trap'', a documentary film that gives a retrospective insight into developing ''The Parent Trap''. <ref>http://www.familyfilmsproductions.com</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hWzPemw75M8|title=The Legacy of The Parent Trap - Official Film Trailer |first=|last=FamilyFilmsProductions.com|date=23 June 2018|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref> The film will reportedly feature memories and stories of various cast and crew, about the original 1961 film and its three sequels. Among the interviews, all-new footage featuring Hayley Mills will be included. Additional interviewees include Tom Skerritt, Carrie Kei Heim, Creel triplets including, Monica Creel Lacy, Leanna & Joy Creel, Susan Henning, Ron Maxwell (Director of ''Parent Trap II'', Mollie Miller (Director of ''Parent Trap III''/''Hawaiian Honeymoon''), Tommy Sands, and Joanna Barnes and even Lynette Winters, and Kay Cole (camp inch scenes). [[Bridgette Andersen]]'s Teresa mother discusses reflections on experiences that occurred on-set during filming of ''The Parent Trap II'', with director Ron Maxwell, among others. Marilyn McCoo also is featured sharing memories about recording music for ''Parent Trap II''. Charles Fox who wrote the theme, \"Let's Get What We Got\" that was the title music in the opening for \"The Parent Trap II\", and the entire music score. He is also featured on-camera, with talking about his experiences in the music.  \n\nThe project will analyze and also focus on the life of Erich Kastner who wrote the original German book, ''[[Lottie and Lisa|Das Doppelte Lottchen]]''  that the films were based on. Luke Springman, German professor Aaron Pacentine will executive produce the film. This is the first full-length film documentary that details coverage on the 1980s Parent Trap films, and the first time the director, Mollie Miller, has spoken out publicly about the original film since then.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Lottie and Lisa}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Parent Trap (film series), The}}\n[[Category:Comedy film series]]\n[[Category:The Parent Trap films| ]]\n[[Category:Children's film series]]\n[[Category:Films about sisters]]\n[[Category:Disney film series]]\n", "name_user": "Moe1810", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eParent Trap: Hawaiian Honeymoon (1989)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Parent_Trap_(film_series)"}
